commit_message:
Hack python 2.6 test with python 2.7

because following commit
https://github.com/openstack/python-keystoneclient/commit/
f4e6f12a714080a1e0391d4891d3bcf0eecfbaaf
python novaclient's dependency patch of keystoneclient don't
support py26 now, and
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/252256/ proposed
to remove py26 support, in order to make python-novaclient
workable before that patch landed, this is a workaround
temply.

Co-Authored-By: Andrey Kurilin <akurilin@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: I6254ce08377fd117d2fc6ee5c5df8279030db3df

commit_message:
Add check for OVS to be up before starting L3 agent

Neutron L3 agent can only be started when OVS is fully up.
So far this was handled by a simple sleep (1 sec), but it
can take considerably longer than that.
This patch adds a check for OVS to be up.

Change-Id: Ib5019148c8d0a7ecc55557426f067c1f76354c02

commit_message:
Added a command line interface for perestroika

Created a separate script build_package.sh to build Docker images,
create and update chroots and build deb/rpm packages using
command-line interface.

(still) looks good to me,'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2015-11-09 05:45:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

@Sean

This should be not "crash_dump" as the API. This should be "inject_nmi" instead.

If injecting nmi to a virtual server, a dump file is stored in a virtual server, not nova-compute host.
So API users will not be able to get a dump file directly via REST API because the dump file doesn't exist on nova-compute host.

On the other hand, there are another crash dump feature on Xen and another. We can get a dump file with "xm dump-core" command on nova-compute host. So I am imaging the dump file will be stored into Glance by uploading the file to Glance from nova-compute. and REST API users can get the file via REST API. So this feature should be "crash_dump" because OpenStack can provide crash dump feature with the combination.

but "inject_nmi" is just sending a signal, that seems different.


I was an OSS developer of kdump(linux standard crash dump) and have a little strong opinion about this.

https://www.kernel.org/doc/ols/2007/ols2007v1-pages-167-178.pdf'}, {'account_id': 14937, 'date': '2015-11-09 06:25:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Support triggering crash dump in a server.

This spec adds a new API to trigger crash dump in a server (instance or baremetal),
by injecting an NMI(Non-maskable Interruption) to the server.

Implements: blueprint instance-crash-dump
Change-Id: Ie555c0da54204d19500a9cae0e6607326fe04a9f
Co-Authored-By: Hironori Shiina <shiina.hironori@jp.fujitsu.com>
Co-Authored-By: Tang Chen <tangchen@cn.fujitsu.com>

commit_message:
trap errors from git not being present

subprocess raises OSError if the command it is asked to run isn't found,
so trap that as well as the subprocess-specific error we were already
catching.

Change-Id: Ieb9c7f3ccc307250847104a7f97cfa28603fcf5d
Closes-Bug: #1521541

commit_message:
Use new docker package name

In CentOS7 docker package name is 'docker', instead of
'docker-io' in CentOS6

Blueprint: master-on-centos7

Is compatible with CentOS6 master node

Change-Id: Ib81c7f90b51aa4721f292988a9642dad3974f29b

commit_message:
[www-ko_KR] Publish upstream-training & correction

Update Korean web page:
* Publish upstream-training in training-guides
* Move api-quick-start doc from user-guides to api-guides
* Fix api-quick-start link to developer.openstack.org..
* Remove Transfiex statement
* Change Korean user-group link from wiki (X) to official
* Change i18nTeam/ko_KR to new i18nTeam/team/ko_KR link

Change-Id: I170359d83a06aecaa0b41c6512a97778078ab9f3

commit_message:
Add symbol equal "=" in several filter texts

Are some filters text that not finalized with the symbol equals "="
(like in the majority).

This filters are in:
  - Project --> Compute --> Instances ("Instance Name")
  - Admin --> System --> Images ("Min. Size (MB)", "Max. Size (MB)")
  - Admin --> System --> Instance ("Name")

Change-Id: I2ee0c51993349b227d3b2297ec5d6c556bacecf8
Closes-Bug: #1520997

commit_message:
test: Remove _BaseTestCase

In oslo.versionedobjects we are removing remote_object_calls
in I24fe19daf6a5c8d234794f28073fd069101d9a11. It's meaningless
to test remote_object_calls in _BaseTestCase, so just remove
_BaseTestCase.

Change-Id: I3701fbd1cf24d05cf0881e17742cc0ce34f0c2b4

commit_message:
Implement re-auth for swift driver

Implement re-authentication mechanism for swift driver in case
when user token will expire.
For single tenant glance_store uses swift user parameters to
receive the new token.
For multi tenant glance_store uses trust mechanism.

Change-Id: Id4d59b25bceab5be4cc3464d47076fcc1c97a2bf

commit_message:
Add ironic-inspector-specs under the ironic team

The ironic-inspector subteam decided to have its own specs process.
Within the ML discussion [1] people showed preference to having
a separate repo instead of co-existing in ironic-specs.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-November/079850.html

Change-Id: Ied5135ac33f3d74a0146226ba242609b184d0bc1

commit_message:
Update decorator "update_ostf"

- make updating of ostf-server code via package
not via the patch
- add test gate_ostf_update

Next variables should be exported:
UPDATE_FUEL=True
UPDATE_FUEL_PATH=/path/to/dir/with/package

Change-Id: I04e4f93b41d5d22c5c62ed1f8dfa4322d13d327a
Closes-Bug: #1517487

commit_message:
Adds Neutron Agent initialisation and executable

Previously, the Hyper-V Neutron Agent was partially decomposed
from the Neutron project, mainly the executable and RPC
initialisation remained in the project. This commit will add those
parts to the networking_hyperv project, in order to fully decompose
the code from Neutron.

Adds neutron_hyperv_agent as an entry_point.
Adds eventlet monkey patching.
Adds HyperVNeutronAgent and HyperVSecurityAgent RPC initialisation.
Refactors the configuration options into a separate module.
Adds parent class and constructor to HypervMechanismDriver.
Adds tools/tox_install.sh.

Closes-Bug: #1520054
Change-Id: I3a25f18b4f3a0621cb92b44eb61e434fa87e0aab

commit_message:
WIP: Fix Keystone's auth_url in quotas.py

In quotas.py CONF.keymgr.encryption_auth_url was used to determine
Keystone's auth_url. This is wrong, because this particular option
should be related to keymgr used for encryption and doesn't need to be
configured if we're not providing a keymgr backend. As it defaults to
localhost it started to cause problems when Keystone API was deployed
somewhere else than c-api. Moreover it was fixed to force Keystone's V3
API.

This commit switches to use CONF.keystone_authtoken.auth_uri and proper
version discovery instead.

Change-Id: I7a576674a3734e12cd876b84b5adca8e3c7e2655
Closes-Bug: 1516085

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-02-11 01:00:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(10 comments)

I have several concerns here :-

1. The author initially moved away from the idea of local storage and now to centralized storage so why not consider storing task data and the results data in the MySQL db itself ? I hope we should be able to store data to any backend like MySQL, Zookeeper.

2. Restarting the workflows has been mentioned but do we re-start from start of the workflow or the specific task which failed ? Aren't we spending extra CPU cycles in re-doing the same stuff (starting from task 1...9 (where the failure have happened)) if another instance of the service either on same node or different node restart ? Won't it be better if we can restart the workflow from the task it failed ?

3. Upgrades : How do we handle upgrades moving from version v1 to version v2 if we have a mixed mode setup ?  Do we have a fault tolerant mechanism to do so ?

4. Additional dependency :
This bp brings in additional dependencies to achieve the goal may it be the addition of local database, additional centralized database, need of restructuring cinder by addition of jobboards (no doubt job boards is an interestering thing and will be needed but if we have options to solve the same problem using other alternatives why to add additional dependency)

5. Performance :
There is an additional performance overhead in reaping the old tasks and writing the additonal information to the database. Do we have any statistics of how it will impact ? Reaping as we all know is usually a slow task and consumes CPU cycles.

Appreciate the efforts but we need to address above concerns before moving ahead with this blueprint."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-02-11 05:27:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 11600, 'date': '2015-02-11 09:44:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Integrate persistence support of TaskFlow

This idea increases reliability of Cinder as unfinished workflows are
resumed after service restart.

Change-Id: Iab60153b58732453e9a422c07fa3c7ab01e1c886
Implements: blueprint create-volume-persistence-taskflow-support

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-16 03:40:23.000000000', 'message': 'Improve message for publish package conflict

Previously, end user will receive a conflict message "Class with the same full
name is already registered in the visibility scope" when publish package
conflict with one public package with same fqn. The "class" concept might be
not familiar to end user who doesn't know murano package details.

And in most cases, user will modify the class name in package. So it would be
better to check the duplicate fqn at first, which it give back a more straight
message "Package with the same Name is already made public" in this case.

Change-Id: I721ce60cb213fc446f62755b3b59523aca5d5fcb
Closes-Bug: #1506703
'}]
commit_message:
Improve message for publish package conflict

Previously, end user will receive a conflict message "Class with the same full
name is already registered in the visibility scope" when publish package
conflict with one public package with same fqn. The "class" concept might be
not familiar to end user who doesn't know murano package details.

And in most cases, user will modify the class name in package. So it would be
better to check the duplicate fqn at first, which it give back a more straight
message "Package with the same Name is already made public" in this case.

Change-Id: I721ce60cb213fc446f62755b3b59523aca5d5fcb
Closes-Bug: #1506703

commit_message:
[Ironic] Configure Swift as Glance backend when Ironic enabled

Glance should use Swift backend to get images available to use in Ironic
If images_ceph is selected, Glance should use Swift API via RadosGW

Ironic also should be configured to use RadosGW endpoint.

Implements: blueprint fuel-integrate-ironic (partially)

Change-Id: Ia71e69f7171d245c12ccbd862fafdc0e7c216d67

Remove disable_service ceph hack

Now that DEVSTACK_GATE_CEPH is removed from the plugin job's
template definition [1], we no longer need this hack

commit_message:
Implement base io.murano.test.Fixture class

This commit adds load function to load object model
and initial asserts to perform checks.
List of asserts will be increased.

Targets blueprint simulated-execution-mode-murano-engine

Change-Id: Ice06713f633fb2e75d4702d241dc6502b1223da2

Fix oslo dependencies

Remove useless/bogus depends and add the one we need.

Conflicts:
        requirements.txt

commit_message:
Allow to define EXTRAREPO for fuel packages build env

Allow to extend EXTRAREPO (which is only MOS by default)
for fuel packages and pass additional external mirrors to sbuild
and mock envs

Change-Id: Idd9e12ee69b5afe9917326a5ab56e599134e95f0

to barbican certificate manager code.

commit_message:
[config-ref] Update manila Huawei driver

Consolidate driver documentation:
* Follow documentation conventions
* Fix grammar and wording
* Use proper formatting
* Remove duplicated content

Remove also stated support for "create snapshot from share" as that one
is not part of the support (see share types note).

Remove share type section, this is completely confusing and needs first
a proper documentation of filters in general documentation.

Change-Id: Iaf4a47256237b92e0d339e1e143e7515c5db37d3

So I've done some testing on TripleO (sorry for the delay), and unfortunately it shows there are some issues with this.

Two problems observed so far:

1. Because we create a new trust for all nested stacks in the constructor path, instead of using the inherited stored context (user_creds record), you can't create any nested stacks after a token expires.  We can work around this by loading the stored_context and using the existing trust_id when the user_creds_id is not None.

2. On delete, we don't reauthenticate correctly, which means you can go DELETE_FAILED when deleting SoftwareDeployment resources which involve calls to keystone.  Not yet got a solution for this."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-10-15 17:24:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

It does raise the question of if/how we might test this in the gate - I'm assuming we can't control the keystone configuration on a per-test basis, and I've not found a way to request a token with a shorter than normal duration from keystone."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-11-24 12:15:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12: Code-Review-1 Workflow-1

Ok, so I tested this and it doesn't work.  Oleksii, can you share details of how you've been testing this patch please?

I've been setting the keystone token expiry to 1 minute, then running this stack-create:

http://paste.fedoraproject.org/293894/44836710

The problem I see is we invalidate one client inside the glance plugin after expiry, but then fail validation because (I think) we still have a reference to an old nova client object cached.

So, the auth plugin will_expire_soon test is global, and we need a way to have that invalidate all cached clients, not just the one which does the test (or, move that test).

Long term I guess the fix will be to pass the auth plugin object into the various clients, instead of the token (assuming that is possible, I've not yet looked into it), short term we probably need to force invalidating all cached clients when we detect token expiry is imminent."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-11-24 13:12:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 13.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-11-24 13:16:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13: Workflow-1

Ok, I pushed my changed which make local testing work for me (Oleksii, I hope that's OK!).

I've marked WIP as need to add tests, and discuss with Oleksii.

Also I'm wondering about the raciness of looping purging all cached clients like this, but I _think_ it's OK because the OpenStackClients object stored in the context is unique per-process, and we don't yield anywhere while invalidating the plugins.  Would welcome sanity review on that (will ping stevebaker as he may have some views on it ref the client plugin interfaces).

But, this now works for me with the template I fpasted in my previous comment."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-24 14:22:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: Verified+1

I don't understand now, why any caching may be the issue, we doesn't cache clients itself, only client_plugins. So every call to client() must check token and get new one if needed. Particularly I don't see any problems in glance image resource."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-11-30 10:44:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

> So every call to client() must check token and get new one if needed. 

The token is shared between all plugins, so the first call to client() gets a new token, and creates a new client object, but all future calls to different client plugins returns the old client object (instantiated with the old token).

If you can, I'd suggest fixing your test environment so you can reproduce the issue (you must not have heat-api-cfn running, or have a problem with your networking if the stack is timing out, also the image must be built with the software config elements, as documented in the heat-templates repo).

You don't have to use my template, just setting the token expiry to a very short time, e.g 1 minute, then creating a sequence of OS::Nova::Server resources serialized by depends_on should show the same issue.

How were you testing this patch previously?"}, {'account_id': 12363, 'date': '2015-11-30 12:00:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13:

The chain of nova servers depends on each other created successfully with reduced token expiration.

>>The token is shared between all plugins, so the first call to client() gets a new token, and creates a new client object, but all future calls to different client plugins returns the old client object (instantiated with the old token).

We call client() method on every request,
for example https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/master/heat/engine/clients/os/glance.py#L72 this should return new client with new token.'}, {'account_id': 12363, 'date': '2015-11-30 12:03:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13:

Here we return valid client too, because of client() call https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/master/heat/engine/clients/__init__.py#L65'}, {'account_id': 13720, 'date': '2015-11-30 14:14:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

Oleksii, the clients are cached after the first call. See https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/master/heat/engine/clients/client_plugin.py#L130. So, the first call creates a _client object, subsequent calls simply check if _client is defined and thus don't create new clients."}, {'account_id': 12363, 'date': '2015-11-30 14:19:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13:

Steven, 

self.context.auth_plugin.auth_ref.will_expire_soon << here we call will_expire_soon on auth ref, but does auth_token update auth_ref? Loking into this https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/master/heat/engine/clients/client_plugin.py#L145 i suppose that it only get new token. i hope, that get_token do not set new auth_ref.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-11-30 15:16:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 14.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-11-30 15:21:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

> i suppose that it only get new token. i hope, that get_token do not set new auth_ref

I don't understand this comment - the auth_ref *is* the token, it's provided by the auth plugin in the context, and it's the thing we're checking for expiry.  How can we update the token encapsulated by the auth plugin and not update the auth_ref which encapsulates the token inside the auth plugin?

This is what gives us the new token:
https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/master/heat/common/heat_keystoneclient.py#L555

After that gets called, will_expire_soon for all clients will return False, which means on the the first call which triggers getting the new token will actually replace the cached client object."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-11-30 15:22:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

I've added test coverage, but will attempt to add another test which demonstrates the stale-client problem I mentioned to clarify things for Oleksii."}, {'account_id': 12363, 'date': '2015-11-30 15:57:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

Steven, as i understand, self.context.auth_plugin.auth_ref.will_expire_soon checks is token expired, so if we update token for one plugin this check returns False for other client_plugin, because we use the same auth_plugin with updated token. I wasn't sure that get_token() will update auth_plugin with new token and thought that we always check the old token on expiration. Now i see that auth_ref returns updated token, so further clarification isn't needed. Thanks for you great work on this patch!"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-30 16:33:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: Verified-1

commit_message:
Reauthenticate on token expiration

Add new config option reauthentication_auth_plugin
for enforce usage of trusts_auth_plugin for making
authenticated requests.
Also add stale_token_duration option for determing
time in seconds before token expiration for considering
such token as about to expire.
Try to get new token if old token is about to expire.
Add reauthentication for stack create/update actions.

Change-Id: Id7d6692128964f4ef35762d43ef2738df0d83f4b
Co-Authored-By: Steven Hardy <shardy@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1306294

commit_message:
Make Server software_config_transport updatable

This change makes it possible to update a server's
software_config_transport property without replacing the server.

Some reasons for wanting to do this with long-running servers include:

- moving to POLL_TEMP_URL to reduce load on the heat engines, or to be
  able to create deployments outside the stack
- moving to ZAQAR_MESSAGE once the host cloud has deployed zaqar

Any existing transport *must* continue working and return up-to-date
data for the lifecycle of the stack since it can't be known when all
servers have switched to the new transport. This means that a transport's
enabled status should be determined by the enabling resource data
rather than the software_config_transport property.

The os-collect-config configuration data needs to ensure that old
transport configurations are disabled. This includes local boot config
which remains on the server for its lifetime, and is outdated once the
transport changes. This disabling is achieved by setting any existing
configuration values to None.

This has been tested on a tripleo cloud by repeatedly switching between
POLL_TEMP_URL and POLL_SERVER_CFN during a stack update and confirming
that os-collect-config switches to the new transport.

Change-Id: I9c475f0c489c67db5895924050186228403f2773

The function generate_vips:
*receives input parameters: network_metadata, network_scheme and role
*searches vendor_specific and iptables_rules in network_metadata and
processes them
*recognizes and substitutes authomatically such words: NS_VETH, NE_VIP
and NS_CIDR in iptables rules

'}, {'created': '2015-11-30 17:19:42.000000000', 'message': 'VIP iptables rules are not hardcoded

The function generate_vips:
*receives input parameters: network_metadata, network_scheme and role
*searches vendor_specific and iptables_rules in network_metadata and
processes them
*recognizes and substitutes authomatically such words: %{INT}, %{IP}
and %{CIDR} in iptables rules

commit_message:
VIP iptables rules are not hardcoded

The function generate_vips:
*receives input parameters: network_metadata, network_scheme and role
*searches vendor_specific and iptables_rules in network_metadata and
processes them
*recognizes and substitutes authomatically such words: <%INT%>, <%IP%>
and <%CIDR%> in iptables rules

DocImpact:
Change-Id: Ic3fde513ea8b1ccf94305d9d25615471f563779e
Closes-bug: #1517497

commit_message:
Modifying Orion docker package to use MongoDB docker

The Orion context broker needs a MongoDB database to
persist its data. In terms of docker, two dockers (one for orion and
another for mongodb) should be deployed. It is important to
configure correctly orion docker with mongodb docker IP.

Change-Id: Iba09ceb6ad4145913dfcbff5ecff840a498f3d4a

commit_message:
Adds documentation for the Quobyte Manila driver.

Adds an entry for the Quobyte Manila driver in the Shared File System service
config reference. This describes the overall concept and basic setup of the
driver in the Manila context.

Closes-Bug: #1518943
Change-Id: I1c8cdee34e923008a54eedaf3720c33f773738c4

commit_message:
Changing directory structure for Cinder clients

The tempest/services/volume directory had the following structure:

        tempest
        |___services
            |___volume
                |____json
                |    |____admin
                |    |    |____<client files>
                |    |
                |    |____<client files>
                |
                |____v2
                     |____json
                          |____admin
                          |    |____<client files>
                          |
                          |____<client files>

The structure was changed to keep consistency with other clients directories.
For example, the tempest/services/identity derectory and the tempest/services/image
directory. So now the structure is the following:

        tempest
        |___services
            |___volume
                |____base
                |    |____<client files>
                |
                |____v1
                |    |____json
                |         |____admin
                |         |    |____<client files>
                |         |
                |         |____<client files>
                |
                |____v2
                     |____json
                          |____admin
                          |    |____<client files>
                          |
                          |____<client files>

The tempest/services/volume/base directory was created and now it containes base
client files with base client classes for v1 and v2 Cinder clients.

Change-Id: I0ac37e15eddffb12d150dcd5b68e0f933712d22c

commit_message:
Unhelpful error message when api-paste.ini is missing

When heat-api fails to find the expected api_paste_config file, it fails
to start and logs the message:
"ERROR: Unable to locate config file"
This message is unhelpful and misleading, since heat.conf has been
found.
Closes-Bug: #1520387
Change-Id: I54a87b10f1f00aa6945bfc131c1aa5dca7a3583f

commit_message:
Allow user to set DIB_RELEASE for disk images

This change has two parts.  First it allows a user to define an
argument to the role that is wraped around diskimage-builder to
add an optional environment variable of DIB_RELEASE to the build
process.

Secondly it sets a default for the test sequence to utilize debian
jessie for the builds to stabilize the non-voting CI test.

Change-Id: Ifbc0f1ce42f3ab9ec73951a813ab0c4a38639550
Closes-Bug: #1521313

commit_message:
Switch to Ansible 2.0

Once Ansible 2.0 is released, we should use it. Updated branch
to be stable-2.0.

An additional driver behind this is the introduction of additional
filters which allow users to combine dictonary values.

Change-Id: I7527ad084e67b5707c4aeeb09fdc9446889d25b6

commit_message:
Fix the parameter order of assertEqual in ceilometerclient

On assertEqual, the parameter order should be (expected, actual).
Some of the tests in ceilometer client were written with invalid
parameter orders.  This patch fixes those tests.

Change-Id: I9a7a81bdb0d9224f2b9cd53b7fb6eaf5ed7a582a
Partial-Bug: 1277104

Also, Cassandra isn't as weird as it was.  They now have a query language called CQL, and you have to look pretty closely to realize that it isn't SQL.  If people were motivated, you could probably read the code and pretend it is SQL (with sets and lists as field types).  Apart from the eventletreactor - that is just annoying code.

The consistency rules are different (Cassandra adds last-write wins on each field), but I think the idea of CQL is that you can pretend it is SQL.

The implementation of CQL also has a lot of weird restrictions, which is why it can't just be built into SQLAlchemy for example (sadly).  No joins, limited filters etc etc."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-12-08 09:57:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

Ajaya - thanks for the cqlengine pointer.  I'm looking at it, I'm not yet sure whether it will prove a win, but if not too much adaptation is required then it would definitely help with the code size here!"}, {'account_id': 144, 'date': '2015-01-04 04:02:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Ajaya Agrawal: I wrote a bit of exploratory code using cqlengine.  It looks nice, but it doesn't look like a very active project.  I am reminded of the problems we had with SQLAlchemy, and how we (as a project) ended up having to take on the maintenance of key portions of this package (e.g. migrations).  My recollection is that we ended up having to do a lot more work than if we had built this layer ourselves.

My gut feeling is that we should not introduce a dependency on an external project, particularly one that does not appear to be thriving.  It does mean the first Cassandra commit will be a little bigger, but I think it will prove the right long-term move (particularly as we will want to do more advanced / high performance things in future - e.g. when we add Cassandra support to Gnocchi).

What is your feeling?  Have you used cqlengine?  What did you think of it?"}, {'account_id': 11428, 'date': '2015-01-07 06:48:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Justin,

I haven't used cqlengine myself. I don't even know how popular it is. When I saw your patch I thought that there should already be something in the wild which provides high level access to cassandra.

For maintenance sake I would say we should go with our code."}, {'account_id': 4491, 'date': '2015-01-08 07:35:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Support for storing alarms in Cassandra

Store alarms in Cassandra; events and samples will be in a later patch.

This patch uses the hbase (in-memory) driver for events & samples,
so the tests can still pass.

Change-Id: Ibe14857e98d63d827ba6e3e182809a3227f7ab03
Implements: blueprint cassandra-driver

commit_message:
Revert "Optimize gate-project-config-layout"

With this optimization, there are now changes that do
not have any jobs triggered. Revert this change so that we
always run a job...

This reverts commit 61b2a572ebcde1b2986666713250b31a6ec900bd.

Change-Id: I0be479d619086e3326ca288acdae7c0ea0f7a18f

commit_message:
Remove default=None for config options

In the config module default=None is set as the default value,
so it isn't necessary to set it again in the code.

Change-Id: Iae2cfaa40e17ff17ebb5f827d6b6d6ca5b370e36

commit_message:
Add neutron-linuxbridge-cleanup util

Removal of empty bridges have been disabled [1] to fix a race condition
between Nova and Neutron where a bridge would be removed if
the only instance using it is rebooted. This means empty bridges
will pile up over time.

This script can be used to periodically remove empty bridges by running it
on compute nodes.

Note: Usage of this script can still trigger the original race condition.
It should be used when you don't expect anyone do be doing operations
on their instances.

[1] Commit 8dd8a7d93564168b98fa2350eedf56acede42b0f

DocImpact: Add neutron-linuxbridge-cleanup util
Related-bug: #1328546
Closes-bug: #1497027
Co-Authored-By: Cedric Brandily <zzelle@gmail.com>
Change-Id: Ieb2796381579ad295abf361ce483d979a53d2bd6
(cherry picked from commit 27f60c314bc9de5d81571de1437f93ca232f1382)

commit_message:
Support Unicode request_id on Python 3

The oslo.context change If48ee7f4d1c113f1f26b3b1698c6b055807b950f
will change request_id type on Python 3 from bytes to str. This
change prepares Neutron for this change.

Change-Id: I872c268ef5f17dc2c1fe0ce8aa7e8af4ebc1d757

commit_message:
Fix status code returned from API

This patch adds a status code 'success' that represents a success
reponse a user can expect from the senlin-api. The default status code
(as implicitly specifed) in webob.Response is 200. This new status code
overrides that for a better conformance with the guidelines from the
api-wg project. When there is no guidelines for reference, we refer to
the HTTP protocol specification for definition.

Change-Id: I787739ab071bfbe70abeca8f8dc98f2e3ece8d05
partial-blueprint: http-response-modification

commit_message:
Check new_profile before updating node

When new_profile is not provided, some updates should be forbidden,
so check new_profile before updating it.

Change-Id: Ifbd8da0c3e27b965e5c2671f536f947150c7912b
Closes-bug: #1521851

commit_message:
Adding support for Discovery calls

Support for the DiscoveryNew and DiscoverDelete methods as
defined in the libnetwork released with Docker 1.9.0 is added.
Neutron does not require using such informaton. Nor is it capable
of using such information with its current API.

Change-Id: Icca7858e2f0f5c686a841f4611b9e2cfc9a47368

commit_message:
DVR:don't reschedule the l3 agent running on compute node

For a DVR router, when it updates router gateway_ip, it should not
reschedule the l3 agents running on compute nodes whose mode is dvr,
it just need to reschedule the l3 agents running on network nodes
whose mode is dvr_snat.

commit_message:
Fixed _NO_DATA_ insertion even when data was present

State tracking was a little bit sloppy.
The _has_data flag was global and not per tenant.
The dates where not always cleaned on commit leading to false
calculation.

Change-Id: Ie1fc70ba0335f1fc351d41675e28abea835082d1
Closes-Bug: #1511206

commit_message:
Cleanup unused test code in test_scheduler.py

In test_scheduler.py, the test class `SchedulerInstanceGroupData` do not
have any test methods. So remove it.

This test class is originally introduced in the change
I539424192727cf2a768d6b24ba9cf36dc56c9304. But between patch 35 and 36,
all the tests in this class are removed except for the class itself.

Change-Id: Ie5e52442bab97b3ef77d8085129a18881591077b

commit_message:
[config-ref] Consolidate IBM driver reference

Streamline documentation:
* Follow usual practice of giving code snippets for configuration files.
* Do not mention obvious things like that a restart of a server is needed.
* Remove optional settings, the configuration table contains all settings.

Change-Id: I21699db334c48f36b2b6a065a129130026b5d591

commit_message:
Add a note about graceful ovs-agent restart

When restarting the neutron-plugin-openvswitch-agent prior to the
Liberty release, the agent would drop all existing flows. This
behaviour would break all networking until the agent recreates
the flows. Now, the neutron-plugin-openvswitch-agent only drops
the old flows when you restart it, reducing the impact on
networking.

Change-Id: I00b06b999e010fc34455b77d6006da7697491465
Closes-bug: #1487250

to enable router.

commit_message:
Refactor deps to use extras and env markers

Adds extras for e.g. nova to use for testing, so that oslo.db can
control the libraries used.

Removes test-requirements.txt - it becomes a single env-marker
controlled list, and shows how tox will access those dependencies.

Co-Authored-By: Roman Podoliaka <rpodolyaka@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: I97ef5bad215abe60d92c3fda4474c48ccb13eab0

commit_message:
ignore .eggs directory

This directory contains eggs that were downloaded by setuptools
to build, test, and run plug-ins.

This directory caches those eggs to prevent repeated downloads.

We need to ignore it.

Change-Id: Idd164c7c8952c70487253e5691ba2da33345059a

commit_message:
test_logging_error: build a logger at the test level

test_logging_error calls getLogger at the module level and thus
a logger gets permanently inserted into the _loggers dict and is
visible in all other tests.
As tests shouldn't affect each other, a logger creation should be
moved to the TestLoggingFixture class setUp method.

Change-Id: I8e988c88cc1ffaf53bd3c97607f16fc2a8078d12

commit_message:
Document how to download the mesos image

Upload a pre-built mesos image to fedorapeople.org. The legality of
distributing such image has been confirmed [1].

[1] https://lists.fedoraproject.org/pipermail/users/2015-November/
466747.html

So I'm slightly confused, why is this in oslo.messaging?

Why not just make a 'kafka_client' library (or pick a better name) instead?

I'll let the other 'oslo.messaging' folks chime in but I'm not really sure why this needs to be included in 'oslo.messaging' vs just being a kafka library that's standalone. Seeing as the 'oslo_messaging/kafka_client' directory seems to be pretty much able to survive on its own that might be a better path forward (and reduces the amount of code in oslo.messaging...). Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 12850, 'date': '2015-06-07 19:57:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Joshua Harlow,

Thank you for the review. I discussed it with several people in the summit, and they mentioned that there is a need of Kafka support in Oslo. For ex, https://review.openstack.org/#/c/176155/, this review has some comments which is related to OpenStack with Kafka.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-06-07 22:24:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi,

So to be in openstack doesn't mean it has to be in a 'oslo.*' library, especially if its a separable unit (this seems to be?). Having it as your own library on pypi means you get to control its destiny, and you get to control its reviews.

For example we already have the following separable  libraries in oslo:

- taskflow
- tooz
- futurist
- automaton
- cliff
- pbr
- ...


https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Oslo#Libraries

Maybe there could be a new one in the above list (called 'kafka_client')?

I personally prefer separable as they (imho) create better API boundaries, clear separation of ownership and associated review responsibilities, and it allows you (and others) to iterate much more quickly (you won't be blocked by oslo/oslo.messaging reviewers)."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-06-07 22:29:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Or another idea, it appears https://github.com/celery/kombu/issues/301 once existed, maybe that should be finished (somehow it died??'}, {'account_id': 12850, 'date': '2015-06-08 07:56:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Joshua Harlow,

I totally agree with your idea. The reasons for making this patch and BP are basically coming from these ideas:

(1) There might be needed some 'standard' way to collaborate Kafka with OpenStack Since several pythion packages related to Kafka are available. 

For example, 

Ceilometer is using kafka python package: https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer/blob/master/ceilometer/publisher/kafka_broker.py 

Monasca is using kafka.py and kazoo.py both: https://github.com/stackforge/monasca-notification/blob/master/monasca_notification/processors/kafka_consumer.py

It's better to use the same and well-considered clients, since it's not sure whether there might make issues especially when the locks are needed.

2) oslo.messaging sounds be supporting for a kind of messaging services related to OpenStack, and also making 'standard' communication way between OpenStack services.


For me personally, if oslo.messaging community decided to support for Kafka by them, it's best (It can do clear separation).

Thanks."}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2015-06-08 14:04:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I have added my thought on the BP: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/189003/'}, {'account_id': 12850, 'date': '2015-06-08 16:09:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Mehdi Abaakouk,

Thank you for the review. we will see asap. Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-06-19 02:09:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I think this should be an oslo_messaging driver.

Its a bit sad that drivers today conflate RPC and notifications into one interface, but we can address that separately to enabling the use of kafka via oslo_messaging.

Are there any reasons to think that olso_messaging's existing notification API would be semantically incompatible with kafka? E.g. do we wrap things incorrectly or something?"}, {'account_id': 12850, 'date': '2015-06-19 03:37:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi lifeless,

Thank you for the review. I agree with your idea, adding the kafka driver instead of creating new API is absolutely better way.

I haven't aware of that it can be possible to add non-RPC drivers before Mehdi and your reviews, so this is really helpful. Thank you again."}, {'account_id': 12850, 'date': '2015-06-26 00:45:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 12850, 'date': '2015-06-26 01:09:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

patch set 2 is WIP. This patch is for reflecting the BP spec changes.
Small parts and test codes are going to be updated in next patch set.
When you find some codes which is obviously wrong, please let us know.

Current patch have commit function in KafkaListener.

To support for kafka subscriptions, it's worth to having manually commit functionality. (when multiple kafka consumers are working in the same group, kafka consumers automatically send commit message to kafka broker, which prevent other consumers from re-subscribing the same messages. 

In some case, for example https://github.com/stackforge/monasca-notification/blob/master/monasca_notification/processors/kafka_consumer.py , it is prefer to use the manual commit function since they don't want to commit until processing is finished.)

If there are some good way to expose the commit function, it's greatly helpful. If it seems not to be useful or difficult to create this function, we will remove  commit function in next patch.

Thanks:)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-26 02:24:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Also, for adding oslo_messaging driver, we need the integration test for the driver. Currently devstack does not support for running up Kafka, so we wrote this patch( https://review.openstack.org/#/c/210780/ ) to do integration test, so any reviews for this patch are appreciated too.
And if you have some ideas how to make integration test for OpenStack(which project/code should we read?), it will be really helpful.

Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2015-09-07 07:44:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

(21 comments)

Your test issue will be fixed by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/220255/

I think a first step before having 'integration testing' is to have the driver that pass the functional testing suite.

You can add the kafka installation here: oslo_messaging/tests/functional/gate/post_test_hook.sh and then add a new experimental job into the jenkins configuration. Looks at the zeromq driver for some examples: https://github.com/openstack-infra/project-config/blob/master/jenkins/jobs/projects.yaml#L1880

You perhaps will need to tweak a bit the functional test suite to skip rpc tests with this driver.


About integration testing you have to write first a devstack plugin that can live into the oslo.messaging code tree: http://docs.openstack.org/developer/devstack/plugins.html"}, {'account_id': 12850, 'date': '2015-09-09 01:50:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Add a driver for Apache Kafka

Adding a driver for Apache Kafka connection, supporting
notification via Kafka. This driver is experimental
until having functional and integration tests

Change-Id: I7a5d8e3259b21d5e29ed3b795d04952e1d13ad08
Implements: blueprint adding-kafka-support

I agree that we need to expose more info to the caller, however I don't agree that over-quota conditions should be considered exceptions in the logs.  I also don't think this will solve the initial problem you reported, this would still require perusing the logs to find out what went wrong.

commit_message:
Log exception when exceeding quota

Whenever creating volume fails because of exceeding quota, there
was just a warning message (without traceback) printed on the logs.
Horizon doesn't give much details either except the message
"Unable to create volume". This makes debugging hard.
Changing the log level from warning to exception for these error
paths.

Change-Id: Id8ca416e6734cf3f472831cd5fef82e7fbe0d432

Switch to ksa Session

* Change session imports to keystoneauth1
* Change keystoneclient.exception imports to keystoneauth1
* Change exceptions raised from internal API from keystoneclient to openstack.common

commit_message:
make generate_uuid return valid uuid

original design prepended a namespace to the beginning of uuid.
this scoped the uuid to a namespace but it is technically invalid.

this patch drops the behaviour of prepending string. rather, it
takes the namespace, hashes it, and uses uuid v5 to generate valid
uuid based on that namespace

Change-Id: Ibde222c91522fa3c4a1720b6a8da81dac31560b9
Closes-Bug: #1504889

commit_message:
Fix Resource.__eq__ mismatch semantics of object equal

The __eq__ of apiclient.base.Resource will return True,
if the two objects have same id, even if they have different
other attributes value. The behavior is weird and don't
match the semantics of object equal. The objects that have
different value should be different objects.
Fix this issue and add some test cases in this patch.

Change-Id: Ieb28aa179bda945686e0d9c2f341c373ce2bab74
Closes-Bug: #1499369

commit_message:
Add full stack trace for parser errors

Along with each error returned as a result of validating a
TOSCA resource provide the full stack trace to indicate the
line of code that caught the error.

Change-Id: I7e7a23005f5228795fe0da7f25ae8a99ada85c68
Closes-Bug: #1521320

commit_message:
Move engine options extraction to __init__ methods

Instead of repeatedly extraction of engine options in
local functions/methods, just extract the currently
used options once (in using objects __init__ methods).

This saves some repeated extraction and establishes
the pattern of where engine options should be extracted
going forward.

commit_message:
Use stevedore directive to document plugins

The point behind the addition of the stevedore.sphinxext extension is
"to document drivers and other types of plugins to make the available
sets built into projects easier to discover"(dhellman).

More details in the ML thread at
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/073338.html

Change-Id: Ib1d4c23a64cbd0010c88ff77b97b1173da302bed

commit_message:
linux_net.metadata_accept(): IPv6 support

Even when using Neutron, Nova permits access to metadata service via
iptables firewall.  When metadata_ip configuration option contains IPv6
address, ip6tables should be used.

Add IPv6 support to linux_net.metadata_accept().  Remove -s 0.0.0.0/0
from IPv4 iptables rule because it is redundant, which allows to use
same rule syntax for IPv4 and IPv6.

Conflicts:
        nova/tests/unit/network/test_linux_net.py

Change-Id: Ibd5830150011361edcaf3b06b01590087f295d03
Closes-Bug: #1425103
(cherry picked from commit ea5474d6051cb7c10b5a9ea5e1bcaeb060695a95)

commit_message:
Fix race between resource audit and cpu pinning

This fixes a race between the claimed CPUs of an instance being
persisted to the DB, and the resource audit scanning the DB for
instances and subtracting pinned CPUs from the list of available CPUs.

The problem only shows up when the following sequence happens:
1) instance A (with dedicated cpus) boots on a compute node
2) resource audit runs on that compute node
3) instance B (with dedicated cpus) boots on the same compute node

The bug is that the claimed numa topology isn't updated until
after we release COMPUTE_RESOURCES_SEMAPHORE, so when the resource
audit retrieves the list of instances the numa_topology hasn't
been updated yet for the most recent one.

The fix is to persist the claimed numa topology before releasing
COMPUTE_RESOURCES_SEMAPHORE.

Closes-Bug: #1454451
Co-Authored-By: Dan Smith <dansmith@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit 2427d288bc017a5b91430ffe16419d47703d2060)

Conflicts:
	nova/compute/manager.py
	nova/tests/compute/test_resource_tracker.py
	nova/tests/unit/compute/test_tracker.py

Change-Id: I553f2e43a68577c83d890c3671380af68f9e725a

commit_message:
libvirt: handle code=38 + sigkill (ebusy) in destroy()

Handle the libvirt error during destroy when the sigkill fails due to an
EBUSY. This is taken from a comment by danpb in the bug report as a
potential workaround.

Co-authored-by: Daniel Berrange (berrange@redhat.com)

Closes-Bug: #1353939

Conflicts:
    (From stable/kilo)
    nova/tests/unit/virt/libvirt/test_driver.py

    NOTE (kashyapc): 'stable/kilo' branch doesn't have the
    'libvirt_guest' object, so, adjust the below unit tests accordingly:

        test_private_destroy_ebusy_timeout
        test_private_destroy_ebusy_multiple_attempt_ok

    (For stable/juno)
    nova/tests/unit/virt/libvirt/test_driver.py

    NOTE (wolsen): 'stable/juno' branch required had slightly different
    means to access domain objects in test case, so adjust tests
    accordingly.

Change-Id: I128bf6b939fbbc85df521fd3fe23c3c6f93b1b2c
(cherry picked from commit 3907867601d1044eaadebff68a590d176abff6cf)
(cherry picked from commit dc6af6bf861b510834122aa75750fd784578e197)

commit_message:
DO NOT MERGE: Extra logging for lxc teardown fail.

lxc teardown is failing due to inability to remove
instance directory. Open files in directory that used
to hold container filesystem. Add extra logging to see what
files are open and if the container filesystem is still mounted.

Related-Bug: #1491563

Depends-On: Ief8edef0df8da1a6ee94aafa9ceaf96da5e3211b

Change-Id: Id0cccdb5897a30eacbb3000e3b4a6b93d42e9a1f

commit_message:
Use host AZ instead of instance AZ in availability zone filter

Instance availability zone in db may not always be consistent with availability
zone of its host. Scheduler may refuse to resize an instance if availability
zones are inconsistent. Availability zone filter need to use host availability
zone, if an instance already reaches a host.

Change-Id: I015143cdf99f2a3a3829d21525869babddc545ba
Closes-Bug: 1444841

commit_message:
Store the actual UUID of obj_id in Senlin database for webhook create

In 'webhook' DB table, it has a field named 'obj_id' to reference a
target which the webhook will act on. Now if we create a webhook
 with target name, then it will store the target name in the 'obj_id'
field of 'webhook' table. Triggering this webhook maybe lead to
unexpected result. An example is as following.

   1. Create the first cluster named 'cluster1'
   2. Create webhook on 'cluster1' with CLUSTER_SCALE_OUT action
   3. Delete the cluster1
   4. Create a second cluster also names 'cluster1'
   5. Trigger the webhook which will result in scaling out the
      second cluster.

Change-Id: Idf2d27d7f16535a52fbf6c59f1c997e4e0728c89
Closes-Bug: #1521049

commit_message:
Add support for burstable disk IO control

This commit extends the existing instance disk IO controls to
include 6 more parameters: disk_{read,write}_{disk,iops}_max.

These parameters can be used in combination with the existing
disk_{read,write}_{disk,iops} flavor options to implement
burstiness.

Example:
  nova flavor-set m1.medium set disk_total_bytes_sec=10240000
  nova flavor-set m1.medium set disk_total_bytes_sec_max=20480000

  With the above, the instances with m1.medium flavor will have
  an average total I/O write limit of 10MB/s, with the ability
  to burst to 20MB/s periodically.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I287ae84490e648062958856b7e45b5b1ec47b0b2

commit_message:
Add "LXD" to the lxd of known hypervisors

nova-compute-lxd is an out of tree driver, but it is being used
by more people. It is useful for people who want to use system
containers.

Change-Id: Ic9e59758917535a50aec0ded840eae6c440cda8c
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

commit_message:
Add class TestServerList to provide basic unit test for "server list" command.

This patch provide a class to test "server list" command. Only one simplest
case in this patch.

Some of the options in "server list" are complicated. And the server object
contains lots of attributes need to be handled in specific ways. So other
test cases will be added in other patches.

Change-Id: Id9fdba8f149bd74187aa42516067dacebc6962b5
Implements: blueprint osc-unit-test-framework-improvement

This will be useful in "server list" test cases.

commit_message:
Enable setup_servers_mock() to take attributes param.

setup_servers_mock() is now able to set methods to the fake servers.
But it cannot set attributes. This patch enable it to do so.

This will be useful in "server list" test cases.

Change-Id: Ic30d750ebe4650244707a368cdd5d622a8f1b8ed
Implements: blueprint osc-unit-test-framework-improvement

commit_message:
Pass environment variables of proxy to tox

When a development environment is under a proxy, tox is failed even if
environment variables of the proxy are set.
This problem has been solved on the other projects with the commit
I0045cb2253a4d102196fdab277462891a886fe3a.
This patch fixes this problem.

Change-Id: I255c047b52a00c0feeadb865238c79dedb8ac270
Closes-Bug: #1465086

commit_message:
Correct disk usages for boot-from-volume instances

Added 'is_booted_from_vol' method in instance object to check
if instance is booted from volume.

If instance is booted from volume then do not update 'local_gb_used'
resource. Also do not pass 'disk_gb' limit to 'Claim' if instance is
booted from volume.

Closes-Bug: #1334974
Change-Id: Id9564fa6b50a2dee927c4e5532a522d6d30fa70f

[{'created': '2015-11-26 01:19:53.000000000', 'message': 'Fix crash when a SLO repeats a segment.

If a SLO manifest specified the same segment twice with no range on
the latter, we would crash while trying to coalesce the segment
specifications into a single request (for efficiency). Now we handle
that missing range and do the right thing.

Change-Id: If13af444ed301ebd8fd34a0d96a330ded648f0c4
'}]
commit_message:
Fix crash when a SLO repeats a segment.

If a SLO manifest specified the same segment twice with no range on
the latter, we would crash while trying to coalesce the segment
specifications into a single request (for efficiency). Now we handle
that missing range and do the right thing.

Change-Id: If13af444ed301ebd8fd34a0d96a330ded648f0c4

commit_message:
api-guide: fix up navigation bar

The current navigation bar includes a strange gap in it due to how the
toctrees are currently arranged in the document. This moves them into a
single list.

blueprint complete-todo-in-api-concept-doc

Change-Id: I3c6c68bafb589887e32a990e0cccf1bff9e68518

commit_message:
Remove two unneeded db lookups during delete of a resizing instance

Now that flavor info is stored in instance extra we can avoid two extra
db lookups during delete of a resizing instance by getting old flavor
from instance extra.

Change-Id: Id6f4982d7cd90b9d212d215382510c70775a99f3

commit_message:
Hyper-V: refines the exceptions raised in the driver

The exceptions raised in the HyperVDriver are too generic.
This commit addresses this issue.

Partially Implements: blueprint add-os-win-library

Change-Id: I05f1fa21540dad36bb4b04c8eebe8cc0b8585c1f

First off, it's great to have people who submit useable bug reports, but having a new contributor who can actually fix bugs is fantastic. Thanks, Bernd, and welcome!

I uploaded a new version which follows our formatting style (which in turn follows devstack).

Using "while [:]" instead of "while :" is just another convention. Consistency makes code reading and reviewing easier. I am not attached to the formatting choice itself, though. I would support a patch that converts everything to the latter format ("while :").

I kind of agree with Pranav: our scripts usually announce what they are waiting for, then print a "." (typically) once a second until the condition is met, then move on to the next condition. There are several examples in the same file.

If it's all the same to you, I'd rather have a version that is largely consistent with the coding conventions we use in this project (we can do the tweaks for you if you prefer that). That said, I'd be willing to +1 the patch because I also see potential benefits in not scaring away new contributors.'}, {'account_id': 13995, 'date': '2015-12-01 19:29:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 15002, 'date': '2015-12-02 00:16:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Add check for OVS to be up before starting L3 agent

Neutron L3 agent can only be started when OVS is fully up.
So far this was handled by a simple sleep (1 sec), but it
can take considerably longer than that.
This patch adds a check for OVS to be up.

Change-Id: Iedb4626bec8d8b6d5e23a0936ca41b32eb702aa3

Matt and I just looked into this and compared results of talking directly to the glance v2 API (not through horizon) and this API.  Below are the current results:

Talking directly to v2:
 http://paste.openstack.org/show/479893/

Talking through this API:
 http://paste.openstack.org/show/479896/

The things to notice are:
 The format is basically identical to v2 Glance (good thing)
 The "arbitrary" property didn't make it through (need to investigate passing it through to v1)

Things that are different but are okay, because the v1 glance api client is used internally by horizon (that conversion will be a separate patch):
 Tags didn't make it through
 The ramdisk property is remapped internally to ramdisk_id
 The kernel property is remapped internally to kernel_id

The arbitrary property pass through is the only thing left that I think needs to be looked at.  If it is possible with v1 API, then we let's look at including it. Otherwise it will be fine to not handle.  After investigation, I am happy that I don't think anything we've done with this API that prevents adding properties.'}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2015-11-24 17:34:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Cap astroid to unbreak pylint.

While projects run different versions of pylint, astroid which is a
pylint dependency has done an API breaking point release - 1.4.{0,1}
breaks pylint 1.4.4.

Capping the version until pylint/astroid projects fix the issue their
side.

Upstream bug url: https://bitbucket.org/logilab/astroid/issues/275/140-and-141-fail-to-work-with-pylint-144

nb: the upstream response is that astroid 1.4 is deliberately breaking
and should have been 2.0.

Change-Id: Iaf2c5dbb92cacbc236083f8f6926a426bfb28f21

commit_message:
Cap astroid to unbreak pylint.

While projects run different versions of pylint, astroid which is a pylint
dependency has done an API breaking point release - 1.4.{0,1} breaks pylint
1.4.4. Upstream say they should have called it 2.x :/.

Since this is a stable branch, I'm just capping everything, we have no
expectation of projects in stable branches revising their pylint versions.

The pylint version chosen is the highest before the break occurs,
which since it was previously an open range would have been used by
test runs.

Upstream bug url: https://bitbucket.org/logilab/astroid/issues/275/140-and-141-fail-to-work-with-pylint-144

Change-Id: Iaf2c5dbb92cacbc236083f8f6926a426bfb28f21

commit_message:
Pass environment variables of proxy to tox

When a development environment is under a proxy, tox is failed even if
environment variables of the proxy are set.
This patch fixes this problem.
See Also: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/191600

Change-Id: I9e18d42f08b97300b52d27652c7b799ec2a26190

RPC request will be captured by dispatcher then sent to proxy.

commit_message:
Add parameters for Neutron QoS support

Quality of Service advanced service is a feature introduced in Liberty.
This patch adds options required for this service deployment:
- ml2-ovs extensions (to use qos extension)
- ml2-sriov extensions (to use qos extension)
- ml2 plugin extension_drivers (to use qos extension driver)
- qos notification drivers

Change-Id: Iefc289a6eee13b9c66f8131c258af982f232df4b

commit_message:
Remove dependency on neutron for topics

LBaaS uses LOADBALANCER_PLUGIN and LOADBALANCER_AGENT from neutron topics.py.
Copying these to LBaaS project, as not used in neutron, and will remove from
neutron later.

Also, see LOADBALANCER and LOADBALANCERV2. The former is only used in neutron
tests (so copying to LBaaS project). The latter is not used in neutron,
so placing here and it can be removed from neutron later.

The goal here is to chip away at removing dependencies on the neutron
repo. This is just one simple case to clean up some unneeded references.

Placed the literals in existing constants file in LBaaS project.

Change-Id: I62bfd6b34c381427425ca2a656e5782087de3a3b
Implements: blueprint neutron-lib

commit_message:
Add note for Virtuozzo supporting snapshots

Change Id3b5bfc946a858f7e6ed710f2b44c7ca63a10723 added support for snapshots
with the Virtuozzo/libvirt driver.

Change-Id: I4ff2d9b6ff7b0a2c8c34df6a32c57efe08ba1faf

commit_message:
PostgreSQL Configuration Groups

Implement configuration groups support for the PostgreSQL datastore.
Also added Appendix section for technical details to keep the
specification section more concise.

Change-Id: Ifc38043aca4b2596dfc7bcccba4a4b67e4586892
Implements-Blueprint: postgres-configuration-groups

commit_message:
Networks tab does not show external configuration

When you create a network you can specify it as
external network. When the network is listed
in Horizon 'Networks' tab, we do not see any
column indicating if network is 'external' .
It is nice to enhance the network tab to add a
new column showing 'external' indicating whether
network is 'external'.

Change-Id: I6d07ffc0d2584bbf8bd6c25aee660f87c385e737
Closes-Bug:#1350237

commit_message:
Cache runtime metadata in the graph (vs externally)

Instead of having the runtime object maintain its own local
cache of atom names to runtime metadata we can just take advantage
of the fact that the graph object we use already provides a space
for node metadata and use it instead (which we already use for
other metadata).

This makes it easier to traverse the graph and analyze this info
when debugging, when doing other activities and so-on.

Change-Id: I28f8fed51fbffd91a517550fc01ac8f5904e455b

commit_message:
Move release note of 'remove-trigger-support' to right location

Now, the release note of 'remove-trigger-support' is lonely located
senlin/senlin/releasenotes, to unify release notes, we should move
it to senlin/releasenotes.

Change-Id: Icdb116fc2a158ae125f6a651d9441b70c330d9fa

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-12-01 02:24:45.000000000', 'message': '[POC] Volume support for multi hypervisors

In multi hypervisor OpenStack environment using such as
KVM, VMware, Hyper-V etc, we need to provide Cinder storage
backends corresponding to these hypervisors for booting an
instance from a volume. For example, VMware needs VMDK Cinder
backend, Hyper-V needs Windows Cinder backend and also KVM
needs supported backends such as LVM, ceph etc. KVM can't
boot from VMDK backend.

However, there is no way to specify storage backend when user
boot an instance from a volume. As a result, the boot volume
might be created on unrelated backend then the volume boot
will fail.

To boot an instance from specific combination between
hypervisor and storage backend properly, Cinder needs to
know which hypervisor will handle the volume and then
Cinder should schedule volume creation to proper storage
backend based on the hypervisor type.

Cinder filter scheduler has hint keyword mechanism, so that
user can specify target "hypervisor_type" to deploy new
instance via scheduler hint when creates a new volume.

DocImpact
Blueprint: volume-support-for-multi-hypervisors
Change-Id: If8ee8800d2258c6cd29811ba4260b2953128d0cd
'}]
commit_message:
[POC] Volume support for multi hypervisors

In multi hypervisor OpenStack environment using such as
KVM, VMware, Hyper-V etc, we need to provide Cinder storage
backends corresponding to these hypervisors for booting an
instance from a volume. For example, VMware needs VMDK Cinder
backend, Hyper-V needs Windows Cinder backend and also KVM
needs supported backends such as LVM, ceph etc. KVM can't
boot from VMDK backend.

However, there is no way to specify storage backend when user
boot an instance from a volume. As a result, the boot volume
might be created on unrelated backend then the volume boot
will fail.

To boot an instance from specific combination between
hypervisor and storage backend properly, Cinder needs to
know which hypervisor will handle the volume and then
Cinder should schedule volume creation to proper storage
backend based on the hypervisor type.

Cinder filter scheduler has hint keyword mechanism, so that
user can specify target "hypervisor_type" to deploy new
instance via scheduler hint when creates a new volume.

As soon as we get public snapshots, somebody will want to put an acl on it. Can you suggest how this work might be evolved to support acls of some sort in future? I can't see a clean path."}, {'account_id': 1678, 'date': '2014-10-10 02:50:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Duncan, I am agree with you about the ACL. There are two way in my mind. 

The first is the easier one, we only implement public/not-public snapshot, this way is simple, so easier to code, use and debug. 
The other way is similar to glance's member, user can specify who in the snapshot's member, so then can see the snapshot, others who not in members will not. To support completely public snapshot, adding "*" in snapshot's member can work around. This way can fix your ACL problem, and looks powerful,  but also buggy. 

We need to trade-off the power and code complexity, then make a final decision.'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-10-10 05:06:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(10 comments)

Please see my comments inline. Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 1678, 'date': '2014-10-10 06:34:51.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 1678, 'date': '2014-10-10 06:37:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thanks xing-yang, some reply in inline comments.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-10 06:37:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

- gate-cinder-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/45/125045/5/check/gate-cinder-specs-python27/cfc0b5a : SUCCESS in 26s'}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2014-10-10 10:53:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

> Duncan, I am agree with you about the ACL. There are two 
> way in my mind.
> The first is the easier one, we only implement public/not-
> public snapshot, this way is simple, so easier to code, 
> use and debug. The other way is similar to glance's 
> member, user can specify who in the snapshot's member, so 
> then can see the snapshot, others who not in members will 
> not. To support completely public snapshot, adding "*" in 
> snapshot's member can work around. This way can fix your 
> ACL problem, and looks powerful, but also buggy.
> We need to trade-off the power and code complexity, then 
> make a final decision.

I've no problem with just adding public, rather than full ACLs, but I'd like a little thought put into how we might do ACLs, so that we don't design ourselves into a corner - e.g. adding a new field in the volume table that we're just going to take out again (db migrations of the volume table hurt, a lot, in a production environment with many thousand volumes)'}, {'account_id': 5538, 'date': '2014-10-10 11:04:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

@Duncan I *think* is_public field will still be required in 'snapshots' table even after we introduce ACLs, if I am not understanding the concept wrongly.. Glance also have is_public column in Image table.

Everything else LGTM w.r.t. the spec."}, {'account_id': 5538, 'date': '2015-01-14 09:03:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Hi Tiantian Gao,

I am very interested in getting this functionality implemented. Are you working on this feature? If you have not started writing the code, may I take it over in case you don't intend to do it in near future?"}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2015-01-14 10:03:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

The other question now is how does this interact with private volume types? Since you can't create a volume from a snap of a different type, a public snap in a private volume type will cause problems.

This is starting to feel like glance functionality - should we just work on optimising create from glance (see recent Solid Fire cache image patch, and the long standing CEPH optimisations for example) and leave glance as the catalogue, rather than doing a half baked implementation of glance in cinder?"}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2015-01-14 10:04:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Changing my vote to -1'}, {'account_id': 5538, 'date': '2015-01-14 17:23:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

@Rushi, Please feel free to take over the blueprint, I am busy working on my personal job. I am glad that you support this feature, and thanks for taking effort to make it happen.'}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2015-01-29 19:19:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

My previous comment still stands, and the things I bought up in IRC:
- What about backends that are tenant aware? Solidfire is one, I don't know what the impact is, but it needs checking

- This is a acl, glance already makes a good job of acls, so integrating this with glance would be a better plan"}, {'account_id': 5538, 'date': '2015-02-03 14:48:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Duncan, I'll try to answer any questions which I haven't till now. Also, would like some help and direction with some stuff.. Thanks!

>>> I've no problem with just adding public, rather than full ACLs, but I'd like a little thought put into how we might do ACLs, so that we don't design ourselves into a corner - e.g. adding a new field in the volume table that we're just going to take out again (db migrations of the volume table hurt, a lot, in a production environment with many thousand volumes)

As far as I can see into the Glance code, the 'images' table has an is_public field even though ACLs are stored in a different table. Also, without comparing with glance too, it seems harmless to have the is_public field reside in the 'volumes' table itself. We'll just need to create an index over this column for faster queries.

>>> Can you suggest how this work might be evolved to support acls of some sort in future? I can't see a clean path.

For ACLs, there needs to be an addition of another table, which will keep all the ACL-related information

>>> The other question now is how does this interact with private volume types? Since you can't create a volume from a snap of a different type, a public snap in a private volume type will cause problems.

The easiest solution which I can see is not allow a volume to be made public if it's volume type is a private volume type. Note that this information is not added to the spec yet, and will be added in the subsequent patch

>>> This is starting to feel like glance functionality - should we just work on optimising create from glance (see recent Solid Fire cache image patch, and the long standing CEPH optimisations for example) and leave glance as the catalogue, rather than doing a half baked implementation of glance in cinder?

I agree only upto a point - while it is a functionality which Glance already has, I don't see why Cinder shouldn't have it. Cinder can very well have features which Glance already has if there is a use case.

I am ready to spend multiple cycles over the patches for public snapshots, and only getting accepted when it's not half-baked any more. As Glance has already done this stuff, we would make less mistakes as we'll learn from theirs.

Also, I feel optimising Glance-Cinder interactions will only help people who have same backing store for Glance. I would not like to additionally constrain a cloud provider to have same backend for both Glance and Cinder all the time to have this feature.

>>> What about backends that are tenant aware? Solidfire is one, I don't know what the impact is, but it needs checking

Can you give a link to a blueprint/spec/wiki which talks about tenant-aware backends? I'll go through them and will update

>> This is a acl, glance already makes a good job of acls, so integrating this with glance would be a better plan

Please see my above concerns with solving this issue by integrating with Glance. 

If the question is 'why not just upload to Glance and make it public there?', the answer is: Glance might not be backed by same backend as Cinder, and in that case, transfer time will be non-negligible. Also, while creating volumes from this public image, a download from Glance to Cinder needs to happen which again is non-negligible w.r.t. time.
If we have the public snapshots feature in Cinder, we can leverage the benefit of block-store providers having differential snapshots with fast cloning mechanisms for creating new volumes out of them. I don't see a way to utilise this if backends of Glance and Cinder are different.


Note that I'm mostly talking about the 'general' case here, and not specific cases, e.g. Cinder-backed Glance."}, {'account_id': 170, 'date': '2015-02-10 00:58:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Kilo: Support public snapshot

Provide a mean to create public snapshots, similar to glance's public images.
So list snapshots will output your own snapshots and public snapshots. All
these snapshots can be used to create volume.

bp public-snapshot

Change-Id: I5123a5d6a15f9b030fb726e5c4ee87f26e3d6eba

commit_message:
Add dcos library

The project kolla-mesos needs a dcos library for communication
with Mesos. This is an essential requirement for it.

Is the library actively maintained?
===================================

Yes, it's an active project on Github [1] with the latest release
from 19th Oct. [2]

Is the library good code?
=========================

It's mostly covered by unit tests and PEP8 compatible.

Is the library python 3 compatible?
===================================

Yes, it uses six library for compatibility with Py 3.x. Both
Py 2.7 and 3.4 are tested.

Is the library license compatible?
==================================

Yes, it's licensed under Apache License 2.0.

Is the library already packaged in the distros we target?
=========================================================

No, but packaging it would be simple. Furthermore, this library
will be used only in kolla-mesos project, which is in very early
development phase and will have to be packaged too in future.

Is the function of this library already covered by other libraries?
===================================================================

No, there is no library interacting with Mesos in global requirements.

[1] https://github.com/mesosphere/dcos-cli
[2] https://github.com/mesosphere/dcos-cli/releases/tag/0.2.0

Change-Id: Idf4ac1c714094d91885f0918dc276b21d73e9e3b

Unhandled logging messages generated from sources other than Trove's
tests were flooding the log with numerous messages that included
complete backtraces. These backtraces are over 150mb when you run tox

commit_message:
Change reporting of unhandled logging

Unhandled logging messages generated from sources other than Trove's
tests were flooding the log with numerous messages that included
complete backtraces. These backtraces are over 150mb when you run tox
-e py27. Unfortunately, while they are an indication of a problem,
they are most often not things that can be fixed in the Trove project.

To fix this, at least in the short term, this change only reports
anything if the logged message is coming from the context of a test.

Also, this change disables back traces in the messages being reported
unless an optional enables_backtrace is set. By default it set to
False and can only be enabled with a code change (i.e. no
configuration setting).

Change-Id: I9452f03bdd5365991e3c4831aa4936de3713612e
Closes-Bug: 1521373

commit_message:
Port run_tests.py to Python 3

* Replace urllib import with six.moves.urllib
* gettext.install() doesn't require the unicode parameter on Python 3
* tox.ini: add py34 testenv

Tests don't pass. It's the very first step to start the working on
porting Trove to Python 3.

Partially implements: blueprint trove-python3
Change-Id: Ide9ec1d2aee84905c03cacdb3ea35d0dcbf01596

commit_message:
Switch run_tempest.sh to use subunit-trace

This commit switches the run_tempest.sh script to use subunit-trace
instead of the colorizer output filter. Since the colorizer isn't used
anymore it is removed.

The colorizer output has several issues. Firstly the color is actually
meaningless. It's based on arbitrary run times for the tests but don't
actually indicate anything useful. Additionally, it lacks a lot of the
debugging information that subunit-trace provides. Things like skip
messages, the worker breakdown, etc. are missing with the colorizor
output. The last aspect is that switching to use subunit-trace will
provide a consistent output format for running tempest whether you
use tox or run_tempest.sh.

Change-Id: I26e9c45f8e674bdb889b6bc65ad30c4abf6e7655

commit_message:
l3_db: it updates port attribute without L2 plugin

L3_NAT_dbonly_mixin._add_interface_by_port update Port.owner
db entry directly without notifying l2 plugin.
Thus L2 plugin/ML2 mechanism driver will be confused when
interface is attached to router by port because port owner is different.
Use L2 plugin update_port method to update port:owner.

Change-Id: If0178887282456842b6078a851a9233cb58a391a
Closes-Bug: #1475093

This patch adds support to enable naming LBaasV2 Members and Health
Monitors(HMs).

DocImpact

commit_message:
fix few pieces of inaccurate information in vagrant readme.rst

The vagrant readme.rst indicated using ssh command to login
to the VMs created by vagrant scripts, however the instructions
uses wrong vm names, also the readme.rst format was not exactly
following the rst format. This patch will fix these issues.

Change-Id: Ia16cecb5a6cebf073aeb8e2da7e40e95256f5948
Closes-bug: #1521312

commit_message:
autodocument commands from plugins using stevedore.sphinxext

conflicting command names are a painpoint, so is manually updating
a list. let's autodocument the commands that are being use by
existing osc supporters.

Change-Id: If37d81dfd57cc79803668b64be1ccd776e319572

commit_message:
Add check if namespace exist while adding routes

Log trace shows not able to open network namespace
while trying to add static routes.

It seems that the static routes are added into the
snat namespace when the snat namespace is not available.

It is better to check for the existence of the namespace
before executing a command on to the namespace.

This patch makes sure that the namespace existence is
checked before trying to configure the routes.

If the namespace does not exist it will raise an
exception message.

Related-Bug: #1499787
Change-Id: I2e52ae0d30da2576d2fe1c459716ff960d276217

commit_message:
Drop deprecated templates/Makefile/merge.py

This patch drops a bunch of deprecated stuff from
tripleo-heat-templates. Once we remove the Makefile
(which creates overcloud.yaml) we can proceed
in renaming overcloud-without-mergepy.yaml to
overcloud.yaml.

Remove Python 2.6

It hasn't been supported or tested for some time, this change
removes it from tox so it doesn't run by default and also removes
it from the package metadata.

commit_message:
Add script so that deployments won't get rerun

This script creates the necessary files under /var/run/heat-config so that the
next time configure.d/55-heat-config is executed via os-refresh-config, no
deployments that were already known are rerun.

This is a workaround for https://bugs.launchpad.net/heat-templates/+bug/1513220
in scenarios where /var/run/heat-config has already been lost due to a scenario
such as a system reboot.

This script is a manual workaround, and should only be executed on instances
where it's known that the deployments do not need to be reapplied.

Change-Id: I3ac4e280a39acb893a8ecc94712eb6265a1236d2
Partial-Bug: #1513220

commit_message:
[Verify] Using subunit-trace instead of colorizer.py

The colorizer.py file is deleted from Tempest [1] and
that is why we cannot use it any more.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/163591
