commit_message:
Add routing and load balancer detail page

This adds the routing to allow navigating between angular pages as
well as the beginning of the load balancer detail page. The detail
page is very basic but is based on both the existing angular Images
detail page and the designs from invision. It includes two empty
tabs that will eventually hold the tables for Pools and Members.

Partially-Implements: blueprint horizon-lbaas-v2-ui
Change-Id: Icbf4396238036b20712ca643e635dd84fe66a86e

commit_message:
Bump oslo.middleware to support CORS in glance

Glance requires some CORS patches that have been merged to
oslo.middleware recently. So global requirements needs to be
updated in order to support this feature.

Change-Id: Ic109b10fd675e61209399e2dea2b468470e6cb4c

on this extra process in the undercloud.

NOTE: We could save more by running nova-api-os-compute and

commit_message:
Disable the nova ec2 API

This will save us around 120MB of memory which is wasted
on this extra process in the undercloud.

NOTE: We could save more by running nova-api-os-compute and
nova-api-metadata as individual processes instead of using
the nova-api "launcher" (which wastes memory). It may be worth
just waiting for Apache mod_wsgi to try this out though.

Change-Id: I2d9ce88850bf821ac3bf8e4dfa35b2a5f2856fa8

commit_message:
Refactor SRB Unittest LVM command handlers.

For the LVM command act() handlers, call them with any env variable
settings stripped off the head of the cmd list passed in; this makes
it easier to maintain patches that add or remove env variable values
as the cmd list indexes in the act() handler will not change, and the
check() handler already validates that the env settings are present.
The stripping is performed by the newly added _strip_env_settings()
helper.

Created _lvm_size_to_bytes() helper function to replace a repeated
pattern of code identified in the LVM command act() handlers.

Change-Id: Iea2adf7579c6aa0341521aaa91b99081e4701e2b

commit_message:
release keystone managed libraries for mitaka-1

in preparation for mitaka-1 we are releasing new versions of all
keystone managed libraries, this includes: keystoneauth,
keystonemiddleware, keystoneclient and pycadf.

major version bumps were performed since we are dropped py26
support for each one.

Change-Id: I73e301e26ff4cf91c530cce8bde0a68fc215b54c

commit_message:
Add option to switch between PXE and iPXE for deploy when bulding undercloud

Ironic does not support UEFI with iPXE, so we need an option to use plain PXE.
With this patch we still build an iPXE environment as well, in case a user
will want to switch to it later.

Change-Id: I2bc88005cd98adf1c01a8d5df23af723e1f1fe3a

commit_message:
mitaka: release glance-store 0.10.0

Changes since 0.9.1:

mriedem@ubuntu:~/git/glance_store$ git log --oneline --no-merges 0.9.1..
f1f79b8 Rel notes for 0.10.0
7b9bec7 Updated from global requirements
be3d7a6 Remove useless config.py file
b709dd6 vmware: check for response body in error conditions
6993aac remove default=None for config options
341527c Updated from global requirements
2142bd3 Imported Translations from Zanata
fdd725e Updated from global requirements
aa53ea6 Updated from global requirements
d59254e Remove deprecated glance_store opts from default section
6019576 Updated from global requirements
845254f Improving GlanceStoreException
5db9852 Activate pep8 check that _ is imported
a031745 '_' is used by i18n
cc36d53 VMware: Fix missing space in error message
c2b8702 Handle swift store's optional dependency
f37947a Fix swift store tests for latest swiftclient
caf646a Catch InvalidURL when requesting store size

Because of the dependency updates and deprecated option removal, this is
a minor version bump rather than a patch release.

The upper-constraints change is:

Ib9aef5f42d4242b616eab906a3bbc70be0ee73ea

Change-Id: Ia628c215291dbcd2308ab61b545e0614575caca9

commit_message:
Release python-cinderclient 1.5.0

There have been several bug fixes to the cinder client
as well as the addition of commands for working with
v2 replication. We would like to get the replication
support out there to help as more vendors implement
support in their backend drivers.

Change-Id: I19e70591f121def9d6559c654f5d0f10b5d2451f

commit_message:
Remove deprecated notification event_type

For role assignment notifications there were two notifications
being emitted. We deprecated the original notification event_type
in Kilo and can now remove it in Mitaka. Also update a reference
of the old event_type in the notification docs.

implements bp removed-as-of-mitaka

Change-Id: I42e68d2b95014fb7500a709de6ecbd8e5f93bac4

commit_message:
Remove RequestBodySizeLimiter from middleware

The RequestBodySizeLimiter was deprecated in Kilo and should be
removed in Mitaka.

implements bp removed-as-of-mitaka

Change-Id: I34596a02fa936bb455a12177d8959c113e777b17

commit_message:
Remove db and object usage in cli.commands.verify module

In order to make Rally as a Service, rally CLI modules do not
allow to work with rally.common.db and rally.common.objects.

This patch remove rally.common.db and rally.common.objects
usage in cli.commands.verify moudle, and make necessary change
on unit tests.

Change-Id: Ic4b264c6ffff6d1f2b8b8b609e32ca4d164d18b8

test_runs given the test_id for a test. The intent here is to enable
a per test view with a graph of success and failures over time, as
well as a test run_time graphed over time.

commit_message:
Add a rest api to get a test_runs time series by test

This commit adds a new REST API method to get a time series of
test_runs given the test_id for a test. The intent here is to enable
a per test view with a graph of success and failures over time, as
well as a test run_time graphed over time.

Change-Id: Id7fe36c3e1ca069d942fe246d688648f719d3168

This isn't strictly a duplicate setting as the values are different.

I'm a little confused by this change - the agent_config template in Ironic doesn't specify ipxe and is missing several options, but it seems bifrost has a distinct agent_config template, which is using ipxe.

We definitely want to continue using ipxe. So I think either:

* bifrost should use ironic's ipxe_config.template

* we should update ironic's agent_config.template (possibly just pushing bifrost's copy up there)"}, {'account_id': 6133, 'date': '2015-11-16 18:24:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Well, the clear thing is that there is a duplicate here on this playbook, so it needs to be solved. From what i know, the agent is the one that is used.
How can we unlock this problem?'}, {'account_id': 5805, 'date': '2015-11-30 21:47:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

I believe this is removing the wrong entry see comments in-line also notes from the ironic.conf file:
# DEPRECATED. Template file for PXE configuration. This option
# is deprecated and will be removed in Mitaka release. Please
# use [pxe]pxe_config_template instead. (string value)
#agent_pxe_config_template=$pybasedir/drivers/modules/agent_config.template'}, {'account_id': 11655, 'date': '2015-12-01 15:05:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Okay, I think I know what is going on here.  Way back in the early days of bifrost, we had to craft our own ipxe config because we had to carry specific settings that ironic did not write out until the PXE interface underwent refactoring, which cleaned things up and magically made the world a happier place.  Some time later on with the agent/pxe config changes, we managed to essentially drop the custom template we as the playbook overwrites the pre-existing value.

From discussing with Yolonda, she is attempting to get the extra_kernel_params option that existed in that older ipxe template as some farms of servers need specific kernel parameters to be passed for the machines to boot properly.

This leads me to think the following is the best course of action:
1) Remove the legacy template
2) Remove the legacy template configuration entry in ironic_config.yml, not the newer template since that is what is being utilized.
3) Update ironic_config.yml to set extra_kernel_params to be set with pxe_append_params, which provides consistency through the various drivers.'}, {'account_id': 6133, 'date': '2015-12-01 15:48:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 6133, 'date': '2015-12-01 16:29:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 5805, 'date': '2015-12-01 16:37:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Optimize gate-project-config-layout

This is the final optimization for project-config and should only be
run on jenkins/jobs/* and zuul/layout.yaml (plus testing files).

Change-Id: I45e04ba78d317b005fa4b82e0f174eae17b5ac4a
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Enable running tests against RAX and IBM

Rackspace requires performance flavors be used for boot from volume. IBM
does not have Ubuntu or Cirros images in the cloud.

Change-Id: I95c15d92072311eb4aa0a4b7f551a95c4dc6e082

commit_message:
Don't double-print exception subjects

We're creating an error message string that contains the shade message
and the underlying message AND we're passing the underlying message in
so that we append it as part of the Inner Exception string. So we wind
up with something like:

  Error in creating volume: Invalid input received: 'size' parameter
  must be between 75 and 1024 (HTTP 400) (Request-ID:
  req-ae3f3489-997b-4038-8c9f-efbe7dd73a70) (Inner Exception: Invalid
  input received: 'size' parameter must be between 75 and 1024)

Which is a bit insane. With this change, the above becomes:

  Error in creating volume (Inner Exception: Invalid input received:
  'size' parameter must be between 75 and 1024 (HTTP 400) (Request-ID:
  req-d4da66b2-41eb-44c8-85f1-064454af5a1c))

And if the shade_exceptions context manager is invoked with no message,
the output will be:

  Invalid input received: 'size' parameter must be between 75 and 1024
  (HTTP 400) (Request-ID: req-d4da66b2-41eb-44c8-85f1-064454af5a1c))

Change-Id: I6bd70b70585722d2266ef08496b6860aeeab1824

Accept objects in name_or_id parameter

Let's not tell anybody about it, but if someone passes us an object
in the name_or_id slot, let's roll with it.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-12-01 11:28:17.000000000', 'message': 'Add gate test for fuel-agent repo

Add gate test for fuel-agent that should be executed
for each review in openstack/fuel-agent repo.

Next variables should be exported:
UPDATE_FUEL=True
UPDATE_FUEL_PATH=/path/to/source

Test depends on ready,
so it is better to run it with -k option.

Scenario:
    1. Revert snapshot "ready"
    2. Update fuel-agent in MCollective
    3. Update bootstrap
    4. Bootstrap 1 slave
    5. Create environment via FUEL CLI
    6. Assign controller role
    7. Provisioning node

Change-Id: I323398d5a039896f3ec8793ba64b6a6541a4967f
Closes-Bug: #1519880

commit_message:
Add gate test for fuel-agent repo

Add gate test for fuel-agent that should be executed
for each review in openstack/fuel-agent repo.

Next variables should be exported:
UPDATE_FUEL=True
UPDATE_FUEL_PATH=/path/to/source

Test depends on ready,
so it is better to run it with -k option.

Scenario:
    1. Revert snapshot "ready"
    2. Update fuel-agent in MCollective
    3. Update bootstrap
    4. Bootstrap 1 slave
    5. Create environment via FUEL CLI
    6. Assign controller role
    7. Provisioning node

Change-Id: I323398d5a039896f3ec8793ba64b6a6541a4967f
Closes-Bug: #1519880

ensure virtualenv is created in toolsdir

Since the release scripts will be running in the context of another
repository, make sure we move into the tools directory before creating
the virtualenv.

commit_message:
Fix pylint breakage for juno branch

pylint depends on the astroid package, which has updated to v1.4.1
and that is incompatible with pylint 1.4.4. To prevent breakage,
we are pinning astroid to 1.3.8 on kilo branch (and pinning pylint
to 1.4.4).

It is expected that pylint will not be updated on this branch.

Change-Id: Ie5df49f5378360976d965df4742a099e83b13008
Depends-On: Iaf2c5dbb92cacbc236083f8f6926a426bfb28f21

commit_message:
Fix unexpected output of pools()

As of now, pools() of v1/client.py return
list of pools whose all attributes(like uri, weight etc)
set to None (unexpectedly).

This patch fixes the issue, now all attributes of pool
should be set to their respective values instead of None.

Change-Id: I083fa853cb3712a7fc161521663a5b7ec520254f
Closes-Bug: #1519614

commit_message:
Added v1 folder

In order to organize better tests, now that that there are also tests
for v2, I added a new folder `v1` containing all the tests files that
involve this version.

Change-Id: I34c55ba1b8d1a265e2b82d1e46bd417ddaad475b

There might be some wrong setting of compute and leads to
exception of libvirt during init_host, this will make the
whole compute service fail to start and nothing can be

commit_message:
libvirt: catch libvirtError when init_host

There might be some wrong setting of compute and leads to
exception of libvirt during init_host, this will make the
whole compute service fail to start and nothing can be
done on the host. Need to catch the exception and ignore it
to make compute service start.

Change-Id: Ib9444752ee837ec52194b343516f4bd0bb8653fb
Closes-Bug: 1447342

commit_message:
Update pinned lxc version

Currently we pin to 1.0.7, but new versions of liblxc1 and
lxc-templates require version 1.0.8

This needs to be committed to unblock the gate

Change-Id: I6ea48a5e692858db846083e4111f3ab68a0ab575

Closes-bug: 1520544

commit_message:
Add ordereddict requirement for py26 tests

Tests which required OrderedDict were failing because Python 2.6 doesn't
have a native OrderedDict implementation.

Change-Id: Id3b0a9126279bf628022dba596d58b9e3ddb2b52
Closes-bug: 1520544

commit_message:
Implement Gnocchi dispatcher

* Add dispatcher options to ceilometer::collector.
* Create ceilometer::dispatcher::gnocchi class, with current upstream options.
* Add an example of manifest.
* Unit & functional tests.

Note:
This patch implement os_service_defaults only for the new class.
For collector, it will be updated in one patch in another patchset.

commit_message:
Use keystoneauth

With the release of keystoneauth we should use that instead of
keystoneclient in auth_token middleware.

Change-Id: Id0876e90a1373ba31e4ec23d5275618149ca36d1

commit_message:
Replacing application_catalog with application-catalog

Murano has changed its type, due to the bug that prevented correct
keystone communication in certain cases.

Change-Id: I81a6b70c0bc829a0ba2f3dd27654985279cac197
Closes-bug: #1514692
Depends-On: Id568c0a59b2e99dc946b1f2f55f6b233fd6a1b27

commit_message:
Ensure to_dict() supports non-ascii characters

When we compose a string for user_identity, we should
ensure that we don't break for non-ascii strings in
user name or tenant name or domain names.

Closes-Bug: #1507937
Change-Id: I485c2a36dd3e12fd2daeda176791909e07cf9c4c

commit_message:
Fall back to old boot.ipxe behaviour if inc command is not found

We introduced looping over all NIC's as on older iPXE ROM's ${mac} variable
does not always point to the PXE-booting NIC. However, CentOS/RHEL ship
even older iPXE ROM that does not even have inc command at all.

This patch restores the old behaviour of relying on ${mac} variable when
inc command cannot be executed. It's still not perfect and might break
sometimes, but it won't be completely broken. Nothing is changes for users
for which inc command is already working.

Change-Id: I30b8c0e4ab076684ea9baa042e5a9a4f44da9a3a
Closes-Bug: #1507738

commit_message:
Cleanup all handlers in _setup_logging_from_conf

_setup_logging_from_conf doesn't remove all previously registered
handlers and some of them may get registered twice which can
result in duplicating logs.

Iterating through a collection and removing items from it is bad
practice and should be avoided.

Conflicts:
         oslo_log/tests/unit/test_log.py

Change-Id: I869f12a7ca8f6672a344159474d8b3d4ee584e57
Closes-Bug: #1520235
(cherry picked from commit fcf3115539d191e3ad166b12a08c4c662ebf5c17)

[{'created': '2015-09-15 20:49:27.000000000', 'message': 'WIP for cinder-api-microversions

Change-Id: I2eb6b3aa86f8f6224dd223a8b8cef34ea15ce1e2
'}, {'created': '2015-09-22 17:14:02.000000000', 'message': "cinder-api-microversions

Many changes to the Cinder REST API require changes to the consumers of the API.
For example, If we need to add a required parameter to a method that is called
by Nova, we'd need both the Nova calling code and the cinderclient that
Nova uses to change. But newer Cinder versions with the change must work with
older Nova versions, and there is no mechanism for this at the moment. Adding
microversions will solve this problem.

With microversions, the highest supported version will be negotiated by a field
in the HTTP header that is sent to the Cinder API. In the case where the field
'versions' is not sent (i.e. clients and scripts that pre-date this change),
then the lowest supported version would be used. This means that our current
Cinder API v2 would be the default, and consumers of the API that wished to
use a newer version could do so.

Implements: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/cinder/+spec/cinder-api-microversions
Change-Id: I2eb6b3aa86f8f6224dd223a8b8cef34ea15ce1e2

commit_message:
cinder-api-microversions

Many changes to the Cinder REST API require changes to the consumers of the API.
For example, If we need to add a required parameter to a method that is called
by Nova, we'd need both the Nova calling code and the cinderclient that
Nova uses to change. But newer Cinder versions with the change must work with
older Nova versions, and there is no mechanism for this at the moment. Adding
microversions will solve this problem.

With microversions, the highest supported version will be negotiated by a field
in the HTTP header that is sent to the Cinder API. In the case where the field
'versions' is not sent (i.e. clients and scripts that pre-date this change),
then the lowest supported version would be used. This means that our current
Cinder API v2 would be the default, and consumers of the API that wished to
use a newer version could do so.

Implements: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/cinder/+spec/cinder-api-microversions
Change-Id: I2eb6b3aa86f8f6224dd223a8b8cef34ea15ce1e2

commit_message:
Make git log messsage to shorter

git log title must be shorter than 50 chars, and git log body text
should be shorter than 72 chars.
This patch fixes this issue on generated comment.

Change-Id: I2b35b627e32e5891fa0db0aa8c9fce664adb5e50

commit_message:
Set origin/stable/liberty to the REF we want to build

Internally delorean does "git reset --hard origin/<branch>" so we
need to set this so it stays as the ZUUL set revision. We were
already doing this for master.

In the long term we should extent delorean to accept git references
to be built.

Change-Id: I2f69207465a953c259d539e557072ef9d5164752

The _apply_filters_to_query method did not handle UnionModels
so objects leveraging it (i.e. RBAC policies) did not have
queries applied to them.

This patch corrects it by iterating through the component models
of the UnionModel and applying the filters to each component model.

commit_message:
Add UnionModel support to filter query generator

The _apply_filters_to_query method did not handle UnionModels
so objects leveraging it (i.e. RBAC policies) did not have
queries applied to them.

This patch corrects it by iterating through the component models
of the UnionModel and applying the filters to each component model.
It also adds an API test on RBAC that exercises the filtering.

Change-Id: I449acf359dd61189bbdacd200d7c41a4a88d3de8

commit_message:
Fix the timeline clipping path.

The use of <base> prevented the clip-path from working as intended,
causing rects in the timeline to overflow onto the worker labels.
This patch removes the <base> tag and disables HTML5 links (which
would have been needed anyway) to fix the issue.

Change-Id: Ia36abfc4f7f2a0d755c16f9d3c825e33a1c9269a

commit_message:
Revert "Add 'mutable' param to Opt"

This reverts commit d9e3ea699afa65ee5175ccda2420a18830b5b349.

The original commit provided a mutation_hook. DHellmann tells me we
agreed not to provide hooks in oslo.config and rather than remove just
the hook, he asked (on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/251471/1) that
I instead revert the whole patch.

A version without the hook is provided as a dependent patch
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/251471).

Change-Id: I200269b9f14a50d1ec92a3a46b65282b8e89ca6f

However

relates to actions the user can on their instance during live migration rather than actions related to the live migration.  The sutle difference is, as mentioned by Daniel, that a pause operation on the instance during live migration should not be undone when the migration is complete, i.e. it should remain paused.

The proposal here is to allow the instance that is the subject of the live migration to be paused to allow the migration to advance, automatically unpausing it when the migration is complete'}, {'account_id': 1865, 'date': '2015-10-07 13:21:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

We consider the pause action something with an higher priority compared to the other actions reported in the other spec.

(2 comments)

I support the use case here, but I don't believe a new server action in the API is appropriate. The act of pausing the source guest is an implementation detail of the live migration action and as such does not belong as a separate server action IMHO. I've proposed using the existing os-liveMigrate server action with a new attribute "pause_source_instance_after_seconds" attribute in the request payload to annotate that Nova should pause the source guest after some set amount of time if the migration has not completed successfully.

Best,

-jay'}, {'account_id': 12299, 'date': '2015-11-16 07:29:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

I'm with Jay in that I don't think this should be an action on the instance.  Instead there should be a migration task which this request could be against.  But as we are still a ways off from anything like that I think we need to do the best we can with what we have.

I'm in the camp of having a live-migration-force-complete/end request which can take a body like {"suggested-method": "pause"}.  If we're not somewhat abstract and hand wavy here then we're just adding another API that requires some knowledge of the specific hypervisor and its capabilities.'}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2015-11-18 06:13:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

commit_message:
Pause VM during live migration

In current implementation there is no way to interact with live
migration through nova. Once started operator/user needs to wait
until it finishes. This spec proposes new action for operators
to pause a VM during transition to destination host.

New action will be different from existing pause operation. In the
case of a pausing a VM during live migration, the paused VM is
automatically activated when migration to the destination host
completes. Libvirt preserves VM state before live migration
and reverts vm state to preserved one after transition.

APIImpact
blueprint pause-vm-during-live-migration
Change-Id: I733f2f178e6a503918d80524a426c04254f66d35

commit_message:
Add support for Linux capabilities

This change adds a new `capabilities` kwarg to PrivContext, which
specifies the Linux capabilities to retain on the privileged side of
this context.  This allows the privileged daemon to be run as root but
with restricted permissions, or as not-root but still with some limited
superpowers.

A new `capabilities` config option is added to the context config
section that overrides the default capabilities for that context.  It is
expected that this will rarely be used.

Note that there is intentionally no way to specify "I want all
capabilities".

Change-Id: I61169d1d27609deb04115f4119654fd3d0690357

commit_message:
Allow sharing of selected item by page URL.

This patch adds the ability for users to share a selected timeline
item via the page URL. When an item is selected, the page address
is updated to include the current test name as a parameter. If
this link is shared, the test named in the URL will automatically
be highlighed when the page is loaded.

Change-Id: I228d58e68ee986f621a3763bba1a565300c79023

commit_message:
Create an attic for APIs we don't support

Rather than delete APIs we no longer support, move them to a
directory that is not referenced in the index, so they do not
appear on specs.openstack.org.

Change-Id: I0c4646f054cbc73bc078e4cef1c12fdc196bb011

I mentioned this in IRC but I want to reiterate some of my thoughts a bit here.

First, I think this is a great spec with some really well thought out points and details.  I would have no problem supporting this going forward if that's what folks would like to work on; with one minor exception.

My contention is that there are other, possibly better ways to obtain HA deployment of OpenStack services these days, including c-vol.  At the end of the day this comes down to a deployment issue, which due to vendor influence and their value-add via deployment model for OpenStack we don't talk or do much in the community on this.

It's my opinion that a better way to achieve this would be to use or leverage other existing open source tools that do this sort of thing better than we could.  I hate to sound like a Docker drone, but this is the sort of example where I think Docker Swarm (or maybe Kubernetes, Metro or some other combination of tools) would do a much better job than we would.  

By utilizing their load-balancers and fail over mechanisms that "just work" and are used in other places (read: people are already using them and familiar with them) I think it might offer a better solution.  

In short: Why not move the H/A and load-balancing (my understanding from a number of people is that one of the reasons they want A/A configs is for load balancing) up the stack a bit into the deployment model?  In the case of Cinder where the actual storage back-end is an external entity, the cinder services are fairly light-weight and are for the most part good candidates for this sort of thing.  The reference LVM driver has some complications here, but it is "do-able", and with some design modifications (move the backend to it's own node) it's possible to fit in this model as well.

Personally I'd love to work on this sort of thing as a community and think that in the long run it may be a better solution for everybody involved.  It would also allow us to step back and look at going back to the idea of keeping Cinder somewhat light-weight and scalable and most importantly IMO agnostic WRT what storage is on the backend which is something we've definitely drifted away from.'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-07-29 21:10:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

BTW, my other point if you even cut out all the ideas around pushing the solution up the stack was that I think it would be wise to visit some other options besides paxos based models (Tooz) and look at some of the other options that implement a Raft algorithm.'}, {'account_id': 5997, 'date': '2015-07-29 22:13:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1

Since we don't have the time for Liberty to get the required changes in Nova to test for VolumeIsBusy, let alone the changes in Cinder check and raise VolumeIsBusy, I think Tooz can buy us a baby step forward for the time being.  Long term, I think we need to be better ensuring atomic volume operations in general via the API and Nova <--> Cinder interactions as well."}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2015-07-29 23:56:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1

Looks good to me.

I do like some of the ideas John brought up on different approaches to get Cinder working smoothly for load-balancing and the active-active stuff. I would guess long term we probably would want to really look into that type of solution which is focused on more of the deployment strategy of Cinder services as opposed to making Cinder itself implement that functionality. My first reaction though is that it would require quite a bit of re-work that sort of strategy really work well.

I think shorter term though this is going to be a nice way to buy us at least a little bit more of the HA functionality. Speaking as a driver maintainer that uses local file locks in my driver, having tooz as an option for L sounds great.'}, {'account_id': 9535, 'date': '2015-07-30 12:42:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I think in the long run what we want is to handle all the resource exclusion that we are currently doing in the Manager in the API instead; and I believe this can be done using just the DB.  But like Walter mentioned, this is a huge effort and is going to take time to get there.

In the meantime we can get Cinder to support Active-Active configurations in such a way that aligns with Walter's efforts to return is busy exceptions so we can transition to that solution when it's possible.

Once we are returning is busy in the API and have removed the locks from the manager, there will be some drivers that still need distributed locks, so it will not be a wasted effort.

It is my belief that if we replace the locks with Tooz and fix the API races in Liberty we'll have HA A-A in M (even if we have to wait until N to remove the locks from the manager).

@jgriffith: I agree with you on keeping Cinder as lightweight and with as little complexity as the features allow us.  But I don't think we should to look into other algorithms, since we are trying to keep Cinder agnostic from the actual DLM implementation and that's why we use Tooz.  If there is a different DLM that is better than Redis and Zookeeper and we consider that it's worth the effort, we can just include it in Tooz and Cinder code will not need to change, only Cinder's configuration. 

@Walter: There is another spec to fix API races without breaking Cinder-Nova interactions and there are a couple of patches as a PoC: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/207101/"}, {'account_id': 7173, 'date': '2015-07-30 20:23:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 170, 'date': '2015-07-31 08:56:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Add Tooz locks to support A/A HA spec

This spec proposes an approach to wrap local file locks in c-vol's
manager and drivers with Tooz abstraction layer to have a possiblity
of making them distributed.

Implements: blueprint cinder-volume-active-active-support
Change-Id: I69b2da52c4b39c81fccc162890f98834f56d7ef6

I know we always talk about the DB overhead but I really don't know exactly what it is."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-11-09 14:57:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

@Don, I don't have the numbers now, I thought we did share what they were at the Utar midcycle, when we proposed the caching scheduler, if my memory servers me correctly.

It was the call to fetch all the hosts, I think it was something like 95% of the scheduling time, from memory.

A lot of the actual issue was down to eventlet and the blocking C lib, hence the need to reduce the number of greenlet workers in the scheduler to improve the performance without the caching.

commit_message:
Parallel Scheduler for cells v2 backlog spec

To help share ideas, adding a backlog spec to document the problems
with the current filter scheduler.

It also documents a number of possible solutions that have been
discussed in recent years, that fit together to fix the issues for
public clouds that currently use cells v1 and are looking at moving to
cells v2 in the M release.

Please note: there is currently no blueprint associated with this
specification, as its still in the problem definition and idea gathering
phase.

Change-Id: Ie52b862ace7801c17e3844d5c9ed8cb25a0592f1

Change to always parsing classes from test_id

Currently only v1 correctly parses out the class information from the test_id.
This changes the default behavior to always parse the class and module from test_id.

Closes-Bug: #1517229

Change-Id: I6340797064f9289a7e861f853c42a763c5f5e2c2

commit_message:
Normalize volume objects

Cinder v1 uses "display_name" and "display_description". Cinder v2
users "name" and "description". Normalize the volume objects so that
both values work as both input and output. Having done this, the
name_key param to _filter_list is no longer needed, since it was there
to work around cinder wanting display name. In the future, if we have
another such thing (like heat) we should likely just normalize the dict
to include a name param rather than making _filter_list carry the
weight - since humans will want to get the name of the objects they work
with.

Co-Authored-By: David Shrewsbury <shrewsbury.dave@gmail.com>

Change-Id: Ia43815fd3d25ff7308e91489645bd3c459072359

commit_message:
Add delete *.pyc command before executing ostestr

This commit adds a command for deleting *.pyc before executing ostestr
with tox. This patch would help that removing unnecessary *.pyc files
when we rename, move or remove *.py ones.

Change-Id: Ifa0eb18a10c7e7ee7e15ce7cc69a1b007a016a76

commit_message:
New plugin data is collected in statsender

White list for plugins info added into statsender.
Now we are checking that all plugin data is collected in tests. In
case of adding new property to Plugin DB model test checks that
this field is collected by statsender.

Change-Id: Iae3f41b839172b5f6d4f79b207b2a19c309b6e8b
Closes-Bug: #1521596

commit_message:
Add colored output feature to subunit-trace

This commit enables that subunit-trace shows colored output. Because
there are some people who like colored output. While this doesn't work
for the OpenStack gate for local testing it would be nice to appease
those folks and have a --color flag that adds different colors on the
console output from subunit-trace.

Change-Id: Iac48591786d10c908d63e6df94b979ded7d8dbe1
Closes-Bug: #1519044

commit_message:
Fix timestamp bug on create metrics

Try use rounded timestamp instead
Check if the time returned by list measurements is equals to
the time in metrics itself or plus minus one microsecond
on the time in metrics
Please see JAH-2328 "Milliseconds off by 1 in influx" for
more details

Change-Id: I5eec8b947499bc439cab68ba511a3b40205530f5

commit_message:
Enhance test_measurements

Remove unnecessary variables in setup
Use helpers.timestamp_to_iso instead of timeutils.iso8601_from_timestamp
Move duplicate code into verify functions
Create 50 measurements instead of 100

commit_message:
Fix ScaleIO driver provisioning key

In the ScaleIO Cinder volume driver, the parameter 'sio:provisioning'
is wrong. It should be 'sio:provisioning_type' instead. As a result of
this error, the volume is always provisioned as 'thick' even if user
wants to provision a 'thin' volume.

This patch corrects this parameter.

Closes-Bug: #1519611
Change-Id: I7c3b0256af3c30c2f375c0f9373646d3f58cd0d0
(cherry picked from commit 8a428cd73c82f455bcb387637c6163797a532f9d)

commit_message:
[Verify] Fixing issue with failures of Heat tests

If you take a look at one of latest full runs of Tempest tests, you will
see that about 15 Heat tests fail. It is because of misconfigured option
"instance_type" in the orchestration section and incorrect values of
"max_template_size" and "max_resources_per_stack" options in config.ini.
These options should have the same values like these ones have in the
heat-api.conf file. So it will be better to leave the default values for
them that are suitable for many deployments.

So now "instance_type" option is configured, and "max_template_size" and
"max_resources_per_stack" options were removed.

Change-Id: I0f46e9b365cfd59905986ceb0229e85984548b5e

[{'created': '2015-11-21 02:23:53.000000000', 'message': 'Excising Sahara content from Horizon

This plugin moves the current content from the horizon repo to this
plugin repo. The code has been tested in a devstack install using the
following steps:

    1. packaging the plugin: "python setup.cfg sdist"
    2. pip installing the tar.gz in the resulting dist directory
    3.  a. (temporary step) remove existing sahara enabled files from
            horizon
            "rm openstack_dashboard/enabled/_18*.py"
        b. finding the install location and changing to it
            "cp sahara_dashboard/enabled/* /opt/stack/horizon/local/enabled"
    4. in /opt/stack/horizon
        a. python manage.py collectstatic
        b. python manage.py compress
    5. restarting the horizon server

Additionally, you can run the unit tests by:
    ./run_tests.sh

Known issues:
  1. running tests locally emits missing neutron service messages.
  2. plugin code for devstack needs to be added
  3. README is inadequate
  4. integration tests are still in horizon repo
  5. local copy of run_tests is heavy weight, but a better solution is
     not available currently.

Change-Id: Icdce2d3e945e612d368556dd5cea1930194c7b67

commit_message:
Excising Sahara content from Horizon

This plugin moves the current content from the horizon repo to this
plugin repo. The code has been tested in a devstack install using the
following steps:

    1. packaging the plugin: "python setup.cfg sdist"
    2. pip installing the tar.gz in the resulting dist directory
    3.  a. (temporary step) remove existing sahara enabled files from
            horizon
            "rm openstack_dashboard/enabled/_18*.py"
        b. finding the install location and changing to it
            "cp sahara_dashboard/enabled/* /opt/stack/horizon/local/enabled"
    4. in /opt/stack/horizon
        a. python manage.py collectstatic
        b. python manage.py compress
    5. restarting the horizon server

Additionally, you can run the unit tests by:
    ./run_tests.sh

    Note: added script to programmatically remove the old configuration
    files from the targeted horizon install, either in venv or system
    install.

Known issues:
  1. running tests locally emits missing neutron service messages.
  2. plugin code for devstack needs to be added
  3. README is inadequate
  4. integration tests are still in horizon repo
  5. local copy of run_tests is heavy weight, but a better solution is
     not available currently.
  6. localization tooling and strings

commit_message:
Allow for default logging configuration to be user enabled

Allows a user to be able to set logging defaults if they have not
created a configuration for logging.

Change-Id: I7e7ce2f7904aefa30db63264d9e0702f0db57513
Co-Authored-By: Michael McCune <msm@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1521265

commit_message:
Add extra kernel options to pxe template

In bifrost, we have a setting to add extra kernel options
to pxe template. In order to consume ironic template, we need
this setting to be present on the matching template.

Change-Id: Ibcf7442b749606633cc03ebd2921586c64f218bd

[{'created': '2015-11-23 12:22:23.000000000', 'message': "test: make enforce_type=True in CONF.set_override

Current Magnum uses method CONF.set_override to change config option's
value with designated value in unit test, but never check if the
designated vaule is valid. Each config option has a type like strOpt,
BoolOpt, etc. StrOpt with parameter choices only allows values in set
of choices. In short word, each config option has limitation for type
and value. In production code, oslo.conf can ensure user's input is
valid, but in unit test, test methods can pass if we use method
CONF.set_override without parameter enforce_type=True even we pass wrong
type or wrong value to config option. This commit makes sure calling
method CONF.set_override with enforce_type=True,
Note: We can't set enforce_type=True by default in oslo.config now, it
may break all project's unit test. We can switch enforce_type=True by
default when all project fix violations like this commit.

Change-Id: I80d91bbc86521bc53272c0ac04100b671fe1d101
Related-Bug: #1517839
"}]
commit_message:
test: make enforce_type=True in CONF.set_override

Current Magnum uses method CONF.set_override to change config option's
value with designated value in unit test, but never check if the
designated vaule is valid. Each config option has a type like strOpt,
BoolOpt, etc. StrOpt with parameter choices only allows values in set
of choices. In short word, each config option has limitation for type
and value. In production code, oslo.conf can ensure user's input is
valid, but in unit test, test methods can pass if we use method
CONF.set_override without parameter enforce_type=True even we pass wrong
type or wrong value to config option. This commit makes sure calling
method CONF.set_override with enforce_type=True,
Note: We can't set enforce_type=True by default in oslo.config now, it
may break all project's unit test. We can switch enforce_type=True by
default when all project fix violations like this commit.

Change-Id: I80d91bbc86521bc53272c0ac04100b671fe1d101
Related-Bug: #1517839

commit_message:
catch more errors in external commands

If the program to run doesn't exist, check_call() throws an OSError
instead of a subprocess.CalledProcessError.

Change-Id: I064f0bb91aa36b689bcfacb6d2818cac27d7e56d

commit_message:
remove release_many.sh

The release_many.sh script is no longer needed, since we pull the
releases from the deliverables files.

commit_message:
Systemd support for nailgun services

Add systemd service units for nailgun components.

Also fix rhel macros condition in RPM spec.

Blueprint: master-on-centos7

Compatible with CentOS6 master node

Change-Id: I4dc45774fba16037e0d4ccd077ca786a18f58ec2

The pxe_ and agent_ drivers, while both compatible with IPA ramdisk, are not equivalent, and their differences are more than just
"one downloads from swift, the other uses iscsi".

Primary difference being that pxe_* drivers default to *always* PXE boot -- even the instance, after provisioning, requires PXE boot.

This makes the PXE drivers' default configuration incompatible with the network separation work being added.

I think it's important to point out this difference in behavior.'}, {'account_id': 8125, 'date': '2015-10-27 05:41:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Only mention IPA in the quick start and user guides for DevStack

The old ramdisk is deprecated, so we should not really default to it.
Also this guide makes an assumption that agent_* and pxe_* drivers
can't be used together, which is no longer the case, as IPA handles both.

Consolidate the example local.conf into one enabling both pxe_* and agent_*
drivers with IPA and create a separate page for explaining difference between
these two.

Co-Authored-By: Lilia Sampaio <liliars@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Change-Id: Ifeed7bf9128281b79d425f7c5dbb3d8c39e7fb68

commit_message:
Add better names validator and deprecate older one

Previous name validators have multiple issues. They do not prevent
unknown entires from passing through. They require repeating rules for
various name locations (cn, san). They also disregard wildcards when
matching only the suffix. The inflexible configuration also makes
specific validators like server_group required.

The new validator whitelist_names solves all those issues and allows to
deprecate old validators.

Implements: blueprint validator-improvement

Change-Id: Id31889f735eb34323f21a91d68a50602351f6611

I'm a bit concerned about adding external dependencies to our tests. If this commit goes through — it means, that when github goes down (and it goes down every once in a while) we would be blocked.
Or if something happens to one of those repos.
Or if network connectivity hiccups.

I'd rather try and think of some internal test, that we would be able to maintain somehow. Also these tests do not have to test git repositories themselves — we could probably only test the chef/puppet stuff, right?

[{'account_id': 19559, 'date': '2015-12-01 15:16:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-12-01 15:16:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-01 15:39:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

While this does connect to rabbitmq, it never sends any messages. There are probably some exceptions thrown, but anything logged in oslo-messaging is not visible. commit_message:
Implement and enable retries on Conflict

Getting Conflict errors is pretty annoying, especially when writing
automation scripts. Nova and ironic-discoverd already have their
own logic for retrying on such errors.

This patch adds 'max_retries' and 'retry_interval' arguments to
get_client for tuning or disabling retries.

REASON OF BACKPORT
The problem was well known for some time. However, after introduction
of MANAGEABLE vs AVAILABLE states it started to be really visible
in automation leading to issues like
https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1212134
Anyone wanting to use newly introduced inspection from scripts
will have to either implement retry or cherry-pick this commit anyway.

Change-Id: Id9720c87ce3846faec61eb40ccf00970ca798ad2
(cherry picked from commit 28bdd0baebeeb0bc05c12dfe19fcae75e04e9f07)

commit_message:
Run gate-neutron-pep8-constraints on global reqs

Run the gate-neutron-pep8-constraints job on changes to
openstack/requirements as the first non-dsvm addition to the
existing series of representative sample jobs which act as canaries
validating updates to the upper-constraints.txt file.

Change-Id: I7b4d4b195fd72bc191824d3bf494d9dd0d628c24

commit_message:
Re-enable zuul cloner

Update tools/tox_install.sh so that the right neutron branch is also
used when the zuul cloner is in place.

Change-Id: Ib50941787f05d395e570411737a32c054bda8427

Manila $::os_service_default for db and log

Switch to $::os_service_default all params in logging and db.
Changes: logging.pp, db.pp and tests.

Related-bug: #1515273

pylint downgrade

Since pylint 1.5 since to also introduces false positive on imports,
this change also forces the use of a pylint <1.5 (to be revisited later).

commit_message:
ScaleIO driver: update_migrated_volume

This patch implements the update_migrated_volume function.
Without this change, when the migrate finishes, the original
volume will be deleted but the name on the new volume will not
be changed to the old id even though the Cinder database will
be updated. The volume name is a base64() encoding of the Cinder
volume id so any calls after the migrate fail since the lookup
fails.

Also changed 'SCALEIO' to connector.SCALEIO now that os-brick 0.4.0
is released.

Closes-Bug: #1512387
Change-Id: I70fe4bd651b0ac87b9208efb5918a4cdaf6f06b4
(cherry picked from commit 64437898cdf58d4d028975155bda3d21a014bfe1)

commit_message:
Add test for package file ordering

Add a simple test to ensure package install files remain sorted
alphabetically (follow-on from the sorting of the files done in
I01e42defbf778626afd8dd457f93f0b02dd1a19d)

Change-Id: I75568871e92afcd81dac2c3ce18b84aa34cdd289

For those who have to dig around to see what this does

---

Config option graceful_shutdown_timeout specifies how
many seconds after receiving a SIGTERM signal, a server should continue to run, handling the existing connections. Setting graceful_shutdown_timeout to zero means that the server will wait indefinitely until all remaining
requests have been fully served.

---

there's a lot in the bug, and i haven't been following it.  it does feel like that instead of hardcoding '5' everywhere we should make this a global var"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-30 00:47:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Thanks; the code looks like I would expect.

IMO, the idea that we have to specify this for basically every user of oslo.service seems to point us in the direction that this is not a great idea.

When the default behaviour seems to be "send it SIGTERM, and it probably won't actually stop, because the children are busy for an unbounded amount of time ... oh, you really want it to shutdown ... you should have set this variable here"

when everyone is trying to ansible & puppet everything, stuff like services that don't stop are a real pita'}, {'account_id': 14358, 'date': '2015-11-02 08:55:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Hi Ian Wienand,
My point of view is that we don't need to specify this for basically every user of oslo.service.
I believe that we don't need it if graceful termination of service works fine and client closes all connection gracefully.
So if services and clients work well we don't need it.

If service is terminated because of graceful shutdown timeout we will have message https://github.com/openstack/oslo.service/blob/master/oslo_service/service.py#L344 in log file and it could be a reason to report a bug(that graceful shutdown doesn't work)
This message could be changed to warning...or even error message.

This review allows to close bug #1446583 but at the same time graceful shutdown problems will be visible.

What is your point of view?"}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-11-18 14:35:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2015-12-01 14:21:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-01 14:23:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: -Verified

commit_message:
Config graceful_shutdown_timeout option for services

To avoid hanging services during gracefull shutdown option
graceful_shutdown_timeout should be configured.

Closes-Bug: #1446583

Change-Id: I2b7f0df831d65c55ae8cae241478f49c9641d99f

commit_message:
Replacing application_catalog with application-catalog

Murano does not get keystone endpoint when Keystone is configured to use
templated catalog

Change-Id: Ib99e649f4e2dc750043ee025fd56d2fef8486a8c
Closes-bug: #1514692
Depends-On: Id568c0a59b2e99dc946b1f2f55f6b233fd6a1b27

commit_message:
Allow to install plugin to operational environment

- Added attribute 'is_runtime' to plugin. this attribute means
  that plugin can be installed to operational env.
- Make attribute 'is_locked' public and remove logic to calculate
  the cluster is locked or not from UI.

Change-Id: I372bfb2c502bcd5927533b03aea1557cf49d9afb
Closes-Bug: #1519050

commit_message:
Reduce election refresh interval, handle EtcdEventIndexCleared.

Reduce refresh interval so event buffer is less likely to wrap
while we're waiting.

If we do hit EtcdEventIndexCleared, suppress spammy warning log
since we handle that case.

Change-Id: Icc0d64bbaf3d99d824a578f67888e8d81f0e5bae
Closes-Bug: #1521638

commit_message:
Allow to set resource type for aggregation

On Gnocchi API, for the 'aggregation across metrics' we need to
set the resource_type to be able to create query against extended
attribute of resources, like filter on 'server_group' for a 'instance'.

This change allows that.

Change-Id: I30dc0cac07adcfcf80eab1b77850cd742a9bb6d3

commit_message:
Fix pep8 issues

Unblock the gate. Did the following:

1. Fixed import order
2. update pylint to exclude:
  too-many-statements,
  redefined-variable-type,
  simplifiable-if-statement,
  not-an-iterabl,
  abstract-class-instantiated,
  too-many-nested-blocks,
  unsubscriptable-object,
  not-an-iterable

Closes-bug: #1521620

Change-Id: I79e070843e3337fd3e480414fda3eb8f03d9daa0

commit_message:
Remove sharps from release notes

Sharp will be treated as start of a comment, so it will remove
useful information from a release note.

Change-Id: I8892318c199d65377343921a03e27d2cda2e72f9

commit_message:
Fix deadlock in status reporting.

Fixes https://github.com/projectcalico/calico/issues/869
caused by deadlock between eventlet and the C-based mysql
driver.

Resolved in the same way as neutron does by taking the
per-process lock.

As a side-effect, addresses an ambiguity between ports
with the same ID on different hosts (which can occur
during a migration or reschedule).

Closes-Bug: #1519799
Change-Id: I8e459d9cd7fb04d7dad24cfd59d8d455fb8eeb4f

commit_message:
add adminUserDomainId and adminUserProjectId support to monasca-api

add support to scope the user or project with the DomainId and not only the
DomainName as i added it some weeks ago to the monasca-api.

this change basically completes
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/215146/

commit_message:
Barbican $::os_service_default for db and logging

Switch to $::os_service_default all params in logging and db.
Changes: logging.pp, db.pp and tests.

Related-bug: #1515273

commit_message:
Enable Neutron's port security

Port security extension allows turn off L2 filtering on specified Neutron ports
This extension was developed in Kilo cycle and addresses issues raised up
by operators who were not able to pass L2 traffic to OpenStack instances.

Change-Id: Idc2abdcfdfb9e62f7cda3f1429ce45cd75c6929e
Closes-bug: #1514010

commit_message:
Override verify argument of generic session

Added config option to support that. It can be useful to
disable verification of certificate during generic session
creation on some deployments.

Change-Id: I99433684c72e10f5437d83e785e5ad5f049f3767
Closes-bug: 1517918

why add show event on mouseover?'}, {'account_id': 13325, 'date': '2015-11-10 15:09:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

+1 for Rob's comment. I have the same behaviour.
With first mouseover details popup appears and hangs. With second mouseover it dissapears.
If you add console.log() on the 508 line, you could see that mousover is called multiple times.
So, I think, thats why we have this strange behaviour."}, {'account_id': 8040, 'date': '2015-11-23 10:52:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Timur and Travis, I have a revised patch that fixes the odd behavior that the current patch has - but that essentially removes/eliminates the need for a click to see the details. Per the previous comments, current desired behavior is to have pop ups only on clicks and not on flyover. Abandoning this patch. Thanks!'}]

commit_message:
Adds flyover information in the network topology

Displays the details of the network objects on mouse over in
addition to click in the topology view similiar to how this
was displayed in the older view.

Change-Id: Ia23da0491dfad4f3b7793c0a0fda678ada9da396
Closes-bug: #1498597

was deleted, but in test for backup-restore signature of method
wasn't modified.

What is done:
* added method for EnvironmentManager class that reads fixture
  by given name and version of the Fuel release
* added method that patches release object with particular attributes
  from 'openstack' fixture of given version. It is needed in case new
  data is introduced to current version fixture that is not compatible
  with existing tests for components specific to other versions of Fuel.
  E.g. serializers.
* some tests for 7.0 env-s are modified to use the functionality
* some tests are forced to use 8.0 version for env-s now

Partially Implements: blueprint fuel-integrate-ironic

commit_message:
Patch network_roles_metadata for 7.0 release where needed

The patching mostly done for tests for nailgun components adhering to
the release version. E.g. network serializers. Some tests are forced to
create environments of 8.0 version. The change is needed to resolve
possible issues with the tests when network roles metadata is changed
drastically and is not compatible with mentioned components.

Partial-Bug: #1517874
Change-Id: I55607157ae7767ffdfd1d855b872630832706e8e

Ceilometer $::os_service_default for db and log

Changes: logging.pp, db.pp and tests.

Related-bug: #1515273

commit_message:
Set correct vncproxy_protocol parameter in nova::vncproxy

https protocol was introduce in MOS 7.0 and default value for
vncproxy_protocol should be changed from http to https.

Change-Id: I6999579a14a9b20dec4230c2b2efe8aafe7b681c
Closes-bug: #1511422

commit_message:
scenario001: deploy & test Aodh

Aodh is the new service that replaces Ceilometer Alarm.
This patch aims to:

* deploy Aodh in scenario001 (beside Ceilometer).
* drop ceilometer alarm code (replaced by puppet-aodh).
* add TelemetryAlarming testing (to validate Telemetry Alarm with Aodh).

Change-Id: I1acde0fad6c36429562d8576663c4cb9d393a79d

commit_message:
Use unscoped token for scoping to project

When authenticating a user in v3, always request
for an unscoped token. Otherwise it would automatically
default to the default project.

Change-Id: I9e1d9129e2fb35933c803096fca9f1236affc27f
Closes-Bug: #1474893
(cherry picked from commit e4062e37069d58814b7c09299d3018297a75ba1d)

commit_message:
Improve release notes guidance - single patch

After some discussion on a patch and in room with Doug,
we determined that we should make the guidance for release notes
more strongly suggest providing release notes in the same
patch as the changes being introduced.

Change-Id: Ifa8e8e9b01fafaa0a7e3e12b0052e4f8d5554e58

mistakenly called host instead.

TrivialFix

commit_message:
Simplify ping usage for service VM check in CI

Just rely on the return code from "ping" instead of
parsing it's output when checking the service VM during
the CI run.

Change-Id: I20f144687662a0dda5fdfc0293ab578009658c1b

Shorten default devstack instance name template

Shorten the default devstack instance name template due to issues
with the 31 character instance name maximum

[{'created': '2015-11-13 10:47:57.000000000', 'message': 'Add ironic-agent-troubleshoot element

Troubleshooting a ramdisk can be quite hard, specially if you can not get
a prompt you can enter commands to find out what went wrong. By default,
the ironic-python-agent ramdisk doesn't have any SSH key or password for
any user. Of course one could use the ``devuser`` element to generate
an image with SSH keys and user/password in the image but that would be
a massive security hole and very it's discouraged to run in production
with a ramdisk like that.

This commit is adding a new element called ironic-agent-troubleshoot,
which inserts a helper script into the ironic-pyhton-agent ramdisk image
to allow operators to inject a SSH key and/or change the root password
dynamically when it boots via parameters in the kernel command line.

Those parameters are:

sshkey = If the operator append sshkey="$PUBLIC_SSH_KEY" to the kernel
command line on boot, the helper script will append this key to the root
user authorized_keys.

rootpwd = If the operator append rootpwd="$PASSWORD" to the kernel
command line on boot, the helper script will set the root password to
the one specified by this option.

Change-Id: I6b87a1b90163d79745f30dfacd37516051fa0aea

commit_message:
Add dynamic-login element

Troubleshooting an image can be quite hard, specially if you can not get
a prompt you can enter commands to find out what went wrong. By default,
the images (specially ramdisks) doesn't have any SSH key or password for
any user. Of course one could use the ``devuser`` element to generate
an image with SSH keys and user/password in the image but that would be
a massive security hole and very it's discouraged to run in production
with a ramdisk like that.

This commit is adding a new element called dynamic-login, which inserts
a helper script into the image to allow operators to inject a SSH key
and/or change the root password dynamically when it boots via parameters
in the kernel command line.

Those parameters are:

sshkey = If the operator append sshkey="$PUBLIC_SSH_KEY" to the kernel
command line on boot, the helper script will append this key to the root
user authorized_keys.

rootpwd = If the operator append rootpwd="$ENCRYPTED_PASSWORD" to the
kernel command line on boot, the helper script will set the root password
to the one specified by this option. Note that this password should be
an encrypted password.

Change-Id: I6b87a1b90163d79745f30dfacd37516051fa0aea

commit_message:
Revert "Revert "Separate CentOS from MOS""

Fix the problem with separate repos to support rebuild docker

1. Make a symlink for mos-centos in /var/www/nailgun in iso/ks.template
2. Add mos-repos to the bootstrap_admin_node.sh

This reverts commit 32b136301591277dd87f3d367c1370a8a093fb02.

Closes-bug: #1521551
Change-Id: I8ef58b581f253b26d158b725a9e366d7f1b3706d

part of this new document.

pylint depends on the asteroid package, and pylint 1.4.4
when used with astroid 1.4.0 or 1.4.1 is broken. This change
pins astroid at 1.3.8, which is compatible with pylint 1.4.4

'}]
commit_message:
Pin astroid package for local testing

pylint depends on the asteroid package, and pylint 1.4.4
when used with astroid 1.4.0 or 1.4.1 is broken. This change
pins astroid at 1.3.8, which is compatible with pylint 1.4.4
and will allow local pep8 runs to pass.

There is no problem on liberty and master branches for gate
runs, because the pep8 constraints job is used and it relies
on the upper constraints file, which pins astroid at 1.3.8
(and global requirements pins pylint at 1.4.4).

Note: If, at a later time, a move is made to pylint 1.5.0 and
astroid 1.4.1, the code will need to be updated as new failures
are detected with that version.

Change-Id: Iae26ba01ddac7c824550a090b72fa162b5cfd5ea

commit_message:
Add sanity tests for testing actions with Node

Smoke tests for the Ironic CLI commands
which checks basic actions with node command like
create, update, delete etc.

Add get_table_headers() method that allows to
get table header from cmd output.
Add 'utils' module
Table structure tests have been updated.

Change-Id: If60b3720e9ce9a6a6c7e35880bf3f9c661d6f259
Implements: blueprint ironicclient-functional-tests

commit_message:
[Murano Docs] Remove logs section

* Removes the Analyze logs section as it will be
covered in the Troubleshooting section of the Admin Guide.

Change-Id: Icbd2481288c159c2310df605d5d2f31dab41356f

commit_message:
Configure Tempest to use isolated tenants

Rally is running Tempest in parallel but it is not configuring it to
run in parallel correctly. For Tempest to be able to run in parallel
correctly it needs to be set up to use either Tenant Isolation, or
Locking Test Accounts, currently Rally was configuring Tempest to use
Non-Locking Test Accounts which could cause execution problems due to
tempest not being able to isolate tests properly.

Change-Id: Idb224ff3dfd4cca9154baabeffb1a520bbb82754
Closes-Bug: 1493147

commit_message:
Revert some chages made by refactoring patch

In the method 'change_default_admin_range' we change
IP range in 'networks' dictionary, which is uploaded
to settings later.
Revert appropriate code which was removed by this
commit: I68ffdc85c2d1289d7ab6ef6a7f4084c19e7afcf9

Change-Id: I99dfed47ca0c6008cbe974a5bf7aa55c85eae7fa
Closes-bug: #1521235

commit_message:
Support oslo_* namespaces (tests)

Updated oslo components uses oslo_* namespaces instead of oslo.*

It is required to support new ones because CentOS7 master node
also contains updated OpenStack components.

This commit adds support for those.

Blueprint: master-on-centos7

Compatible with CentOS6 master node

Change-Id: I6216961d8bccad75e32778bfaa51bc07a30c7f7c

[{'created': '2015-11-25 05:49:49.000000000', 'message': "Add backlog for release notes during mitaka

This patch adds some release notes items we haven't been documenting so
far. In future, release note items are supposed to be proposed along
with a bug-fix or feature patch when appropriate. To do that, you will
need to first 'pip install reno' as preparation then:

 reno new <release-note-item>
 vi releasenotes/notes/<release-note-item>-<uid>.yaml
 git add releasenotes/notes/<release-note-item>-<uid>.yaml
 git commit --amend

Change-Id: I090105d870dd0c4c207a0e2a7c5acafc49725b05
"}]
commit_message:
Add backlog for release notes during mitaka

This patch adds some release notes items we haven't been documenting so
far. In future, release note items are supposed to be proposed along
with a bug-fix or feature patch when appropriate. To do that, you will
need to first 'pip install reno' as preparation then:

 reno new <release-note-item>
 vi releasenotes/notes/<release-note-item>-<uid>.yaml
 git add releasenotes/notes/<release-note-item>-<uid>.yaml
 git commit --amend

Change-Id: I090105d870dd0c4c207a0e2a7c5acafc49725b05

  Addresses allocated like this are not constrained to be in the range
  given by the --dhcp-range option, but they must be in the same subnet
  as some valid dhcp-range.

This confusingly-worded datum means that even when dhcp-host is
defined, which we do when setting inventory_dhcp=true, we need to
specify some kind of dhcp-range. There are a few valid arguments we

commit_message:
Provide dhcp-range even for static inventory

The dnsmasq man page says, regarding the dhcp-host option:

  Addresses allocated like this are not constrained to be in the range
  given by the --dhcp-range option, but they must be in the same subnet
  as some valid dhcp-range.

This confusingly-worded datum means that even when dhcp-host is
defined, which we do when setting inventory_dhcp=true, we need to
specify some kind of dhcp-range. There are a few valid arguments we
could supply to the dhcp-range parameter, but the easiest is just to go
back to using the existing dhcp_pool_{start,end} parameters, from which
dnsmasq will infer a subnet.

An alternative to this is to be more strict by using the 'static'
keyword for dhcp-range. We would still need to specify the
dhcp_pool_start value, which is a required argument for dhcp-range.

Change-Id: I4d09c3a716b864c0b0d74cc83a2f0ac7414b386c

commit_message:
Add note for dropping InstanceV1 objects

Commit 1337890ace918fa2555046c01c8624be014ce2d8 removed InstanceV1 objects.
We need to provide a note for that, even if that's only for CDs.

Change-Id: I4b349c2e02323a6aa04d45534055dccfc3e1be8f

commit_message:
Updates monasca based autoscaling template with metadata

Monasca based auto-scaling needs the metadata scale_group
in order to find the statistics of scale group resources
measurements.

Change-Id: I5cd5ceb95d84b6ab003c8db96fd604ab375a8f8b

commit_message:
tests: increase MySQL max connections

Depending on the number of tests running in parallel, the number of
MySQL connection used can go pretty high since it's used both by the
index and by tooz.

Let's bump this limit since on the gate we have 8 CPU and therefore up
to 8 process running tests with each several threads trying to lock
various metric for upgrade or writing.

Change-Id: I7d6d5dba3975d8359bc1b28f4804d642361687de

commit_message:
Add flag for test_incremental_backup

Forced creation of incremental backup is not
implemented in old release (Juno and Kilo).
The test is skipped by default for Juno and Kilo gates.
Need to add flag to unskip this test in new release.

New test: Idde2c14aba78382b1063ce20269f4832f9fdd583
Change-Id: I565b5941d6067644fc9ca6cb0891d97f4946e031
Partial-Bug: #1506394

Evgeniy, I agree that they should be user specific, but let's do it the same way it is done for cluster-level UI settings. Per-user settings is a different story and should be done separately for both types of settings. By blocking this change you're preventing 8.0 to get any persistence for these settings at all."}, {'account_id': 8749, 'date': '2015-11-26 09:57:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Hi Vitaly,

>> Per-user settings is a different story and should be done separately for both types of settings.

It's not a different story, it's a proper way to solve this problem, which we've discussed several month ago.

>> By blocking this change you're preventing 8.0 to get any persistence for these settings at all.

I'm not blocking this change at all, I've expressed my concerns and put -1, because this solution has UX problems with no clear upgrade path. If you or any of developers think that this is fine, you can continue review/merge process."}, {'account_id': 8766, 'date': '2015-11-26 10:17:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 8735, 'date': '2015-11-26 10:45:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

> It's not a different story, it's a proper way to solve this problem, which we've discussed several month ago.

It is a proper way to solve this problem, but still also a different story. Do you want these settings to be stored in keystone while cluster-level settings will remain as they are? I think it's a bigger evil. Look at our PUT handlers: they mostly behave like PATCH handlers. Should we fix it? Yes. Should we start introducing new handlers which use PATCH methods while old ones are still using PUT? Definitely no. Making our methods comply with REST is a separate story. Same here.

> If you or any of developers think that this is fine, you can continue review/merge process.

Well, speaking of me, if I see -1 from a core reviewer, I don't even start reviewing a request. I believe python cores behave the same way."}, {'account_id': 10959, 'date': '2015-11-26 11:55:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Evgeniy,

> I completely don't understand how put/patch is related to the fact, that with this patch new feature is introduced, where data are stored in a wrong place, and as I said without clear path to change it in the future.

Let me explain it more thoroughly then. Some time ago we figured out that lots of our handler use PUT method the way PATCH method should work. Yep, it's a tech debt and should be fixed. But you don't -1 patches with new handlers where PUT behaves the way it behaves in all other handler (wrong way), don't you? Because adding a new feature is another story, and making our handlers REST-compliant is another story. And mixing both approaches is a much greater evil.

The same here - we already have cluster settings stored in cluster model. These settings have exactly the same schema. I agree we need to store them in keystone to enable multi-user support, but since we already have cluster-level settings in the same format, let's use the same approach and then move both types of settings to keystone - as a part of another activity."}, {'account_id': 8766, 'date': '2015-11-26 18:13:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-27 10:49:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Verified-1

commit_message:
Store settings of Fuel UI Nodes page in DB

"settings" attribute of "master_node_settings" DB model
extended with "ui_settings" property to store
node list configuration from Nodes page in Fuel UI

Related to blueprint view-all-nodes

Co-Authored-By: Alexander Kislitsky <akislitsky@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: I4900c88a02877c4d621e8e835c9aa97097c01fb4

commit_message:
Using 'ready_statuses' instead of 'is_ready'

We are replacing wait_for by wait_for_status now. Changes in this patch
could be apply first, because those changes don't need changes in
wait_for_status function now.

Change-Id: I5240b9df9099208bb847255c9e3ce956f9f718d3

Fix the problem with separate repos to support rebuild docker

1. Make a symlink for mos-centos in /var/www/nailgun in iso/ks.template

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-12-01 10:08:25.000000000', 'message': 'Adjust the RabbitMQ kernel net_ticktime parameter

W/o this fix, the situation is possible when some
arbitrary queue masters got stuck due to high
short-time CPU load spikes ending up in the
rabbitmqctl hanged and affected rabbit node erased
and restarted by OCF monitor logic of the related
pacemaker RA.

This is an issue as it seems that Oslo.messaging yet
to be in a good shape to survive this short-time
outage of underlying AMQP layer without disrupting
interrupted RPC calls being executed.

The workaround is to reduce the net_ticktime kernel
parameter from default 60 seconds to 10 seconds.
What would allow the RabbitMQ cluster to better detect
short-time partitions and autoheal them. And when the
partition has been detected and healed, the rabbitmqctl
would not hang hopefully as stucked queue masters will
be recovered.

Partial-bug: #1460762

Change-Id: I3aa47b51ae080bb4a8b298c61a629ac8225d2abd
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
(cherry picked from commit 3ffae36b9de967747a1cc1045eae0923d6bd893c)
'}]
commit_message:
Adjust the RabbitMQ kernel net_ticktime parameter

W/o this fix, the situation is possible when some
arbitrary queue masters got stuck due to high
short-time CPU load spikes ending up in the
rabbitmqctl hanged and affected rabbit node erased
and restarted by OCF monitor logic of the related
pacemaker RA.

This is an issue as it seems that Oslo.messaging yet
to be in a good shape to survive this short-time
outage of underlying AMQP layer without disrupting
interrupted RPC calls being executed.

The workaround is to reduce the net_ticktime kernel
parameter from default 60 seconds to 10 seconds.
What would allow the RabbitMQ cluster to better detect
short-time partitions and autoheal them. And when the
partition has been detected and healed, the rabbitmqctl
would not hang hopefully as stucked queue masters will
be recovered.

Partial-bug: #1460762

Change-Id: I3aa47b51ae080bb4a8b298c61a629ac8225d2abd
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
(cherry picked from commit 3ffae36b9de967747a1cc1045eae0923d6bd893c)

commit_message:
Allow method set_override with parameter override=None for all types

Method set_override will check parameter override's type when
enforce_type=True, If parameter override with value None, it doesn't
work for some types like IntOpt, or doesn't work properly for StrOpt.
For IntOpt, it raise TypeError, and For StrOpt, it convert None to
string 'None', that's not we expect.

Closes-Bug: #1515230
Change-Id: I42ceeccf59111057b5a92c849c9bb5f83255b324

commit_message:
Add functional testing of CSV file parsing

The CSV file parsing feature of bifrost is ultimately the most logic
heavy feature of the inventory and thus sensitive to change.

As a result, we need test supplying input and see if our expected
output results. Variations added including base ssh/vm testing,
ipmi with and without bridging, and if a DHCP address is defined.
Testing the results of these combonations should help identify any
changes to the CSV parsing that may break users.

As part of this, it was realized the CSV example lacks a driver filed
example, and minor tweak of the unit testing file.

Change-Id: Id50db2387dac32a9c16e927db309a32a7806d7cc
Partial-Bug: 1499801

commit_message:
Remove Python 2.6 workround for logging

You can find why we add it in [1], we don't support Python 2.6 any more,
so we can remove the workaround now.
[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56093/8/openstack/common/gettextutils.py

Change-Id: I5b67e3fcadbdd38f6e92e79f6549af5bafec29e4

commit_message:
Add database indices to improve query performance

Database queries are slow as the number of records grew because indices are
not created to optimize query filters.

Change-Id: Ib31d47d3198e1ac1c02a448f28cd9ac5f3106064
Closes-Bug: #1505664
(cherry picked from commit 2fb4c290766cf4b693ee8f1272e191d6178441fe)

commit_message:
Add list of supported stores to help

The glance-api.conf help is autogenerated from the glance_store
help.

To display the full list of stores available for the 'stores'
parameter in the glance_store section of glance-api.conf add
them to the relevant glance_store help comment.

Change-Id: Ie69e1db0959e22e07a47943874b6710a063fbc1d
Partial-bug: 1521236

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 12356, 'date': '2015-09-25 09:20:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-09-25 11:03:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Hi,

Thank Pavlo for the patch. Code wise it looks fine but I want to understand why we should not be using matchers for such assertions. In my head I recall it being suggested as the right way to do it, so I'm adding @lifeless to the review to see if he can clarify (because I think the was the one that suggested it in the first place... Sorry if it wasn't).

Also I know it has 3 +2 already, but I think it's important to have a reason to do someone clearly specified in the commit message."}, {'account_id': 9542, 'date': '2015-09-28 15:11:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-09-28 23:08:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Lucas,

Not sure if @lifeless will respond.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-29 08:31:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 9542, 'date': '2015-10-05 06:48:40.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-05 07:01:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-ironic-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/60/224560/2/check/gate-ironic-pep8/7efdd53/ : SUCCESS in 5m 34s
- gate-ironic-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/60/224560/2/check/gate-ironic-docs/cf27ef2//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 9m 25s
